r         = [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019]]\n | name         = [[2019 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]]\n | overall      = 4\u20135\n | conference   = 3\u20134\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = \n | ranking2     = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Florida State\n | overall    = 9\u201312\n | confrecord = 6\u20139\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic Owls]]\n | conf      = [[Conference USA]]\n | startyear = 2020\n | endyear   = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2020 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2020]]\n | name         = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]] <!-- Link to be updated when 2020 FAU football available -->\n | overall      = 0\u20130 \n | conference   = 0\u20130\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = \n | ranking2     = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Florida Atlantic\n | overall    = 0\u20130\n | confrecord = 0\u20130\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 56\u201362 <!-- As of games through 11/2/19 -->\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = two\n | polltype = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|College football}}\n* [http://seminoles.com/staff/willie-taggart/ Florida State profile]\n\n{{Conference USA football coach navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers quarterback navbox}}\n{{WKU Hilltoppers football coach navbox}}\n{{South Florida Bulls football coach navbox}}\n{{Oregon Ducks football coach navbox}}\n{{Florida State Seminoles football coach navbox}}\n{{Florida Atlantic Owls football coach navbox}}\n{{2002 WKU Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taggart, Willie}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic Owls football coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles football coaches]]\n[[Category:South Florida Bulls football coaches]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Stanford Cardinal football coaches]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bradenton, Florida]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:African-American coaches of American football]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name               = Willie Taggart\n| image              = Coach Taggart FSU.jpg\n| caption            = Taggart at a press conference at Florida State in 2017\n| current_title      = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team       = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]]\n| current_conference = [[Conference USA|C-USA]]\n| current_record     = 0\u20130\n| contract           = $750,000<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/article238316628.html |title=How much is FAU paying Willie Taggart? Here are the details on his contract. |last=Dill |first=Jason |date=December 12, 2019 |website=www.miamiherald.com |publisher=The Miami Herald |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1976|8|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bradenton, Florida]]\n| alma_mater         =\n| player_years1      = 1994\u20131998\n| player_team1       = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]]\n| player_positions   = [[Quarterback]]\n| coach_years1       = 1999\n| coach_team1        = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]] (WR)\n| coach_years2       = 2000\n| coach_team2        = Western Kentucky (QB)\n| coach_years3       = 2001\u20132002\n| coach_team3        = Western Kentucky (Co-OC/QB)\n| coach_years4       = 2003\u20132006\n| coach_team4        = Western Kentucky (AHC/QB)\n| coach_years5       = 2007\u20132009\n| coach_team5        = [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]] (RB)\n| coach_years6       = 2010\u20132012\n| coach_team6        = Western Kentucky\n| coach_years7       = 2013\u20132016\n| coach_team7        = [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| coach_years8       = 2017\n| coach_team8        = [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]]\n| coach_years9       = 2018\u20132019\n| coach_team9        = [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| coach_years10      = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team10       = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]]\n| overall_record     = 56\u201362 <!-- As of games through 11/2/19 -->\n| bowl_record        = 0\u20131\n}}\n'''Willie Taggart'''<ref name=\":0\">{{citation|title=Personnel Changes|url=https://digitalcommons.wku.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2995&context=dlsc_ua_records|work=On Campus|volume=10|issue=7|page=23|year=2000|publisher=[[Western Kentucky University]]}}</ref> (born August 27, 1976) is an [[American football]] college coach who is the head coach at [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic University]] (FAU). Taggart most recently served as the head coach at [[Florida State University]].  He has held the head coach position at four NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision programs:  [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]] (2009 to 2012 seasons);  [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]] (2013 to 2016 seasons);  [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (2017 season);  and [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] (2018 season and part of the 2019 season -- through November 3, 2019).  At all four schools, he was the first African-American to be hired as the head coach.\n\n==Playing career==\n===High school career===\nTaggart was a prep standout at [[Manatee High School]] in [[Bradenton, Florida]], where he was a first team all-state and all-conference selection as a senior after guiding the Hurricanes to the state 5A Championship game. He helped lead the [[high school football|football]] team to the state title his junior season and helped the school post a 26\u20134 record during that two-year span, while recording more than 3,000 yards passing and 975 yards on the ground.\n\n===College career===\nAfter high school, Taggart became a star [[quarterback]] for the Western Kentucky University (WKU) Hilltoppers from 1995 through 1998, being one of only three WKU players in the previous 50 years to be a four-year starter at the position and one of only four Hilltoppers players to have his jersey retired. In each of his last two collegiate seasons, he was a finalist for the prestigious [[Walter Payton Award]], which is an honor given annually to the top offensive player in I-AA football. Taggart finished fourth in the balloting in 1997 and seventh as a senior the following year. An All-American as a senior, he was also the 1998 I-AA Independents\u2019 Offensive Player of the Year. Taggart was recruited to WKU by [[Jim Harbaugh]] to play for his father, [[Jack Harbaugh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tampa.cbslocal.com/2012/12/08/get-to-know-willie-taggart/|title=Get To Know Willie Taggart|date=December 8, 2012|website=[[WTSP]]|url-status=live|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Early coaching years===\nAfter graduating from WKU in 1998, Taggart stayed on at the school as an assistant through 2006, serving as co-offensive coordinator under [[Jack Harbaugh]] on the Hilltoppers' 2002 [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|Division I-AA national champions]]. He also worked alongside Harbaugh's son [[Jim Harbaugh|Jim]],<ref name=Announcement>{{cite press release|url=http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&ATCLID=204838864&DB_OEM_ID=5400 |title=WKU Names Willie Taggart New Head Football Coach |publisher=Western Kentucky University Department of Athletics |date=November 23, 2009 |accessdate=November 23, 2009}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=December 2019}} who had been an unpaid certified assistant coach under his father in the final years of his [[National Football League|NFL]] career.\n\nWhen Jim Harbaugh was named head coach of the [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford Cardinal football team]] following the [[2006 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2006 season]], he hired Taggart as his running backs coach. Taggart served in that role for the next two seasons, developing [[Doak Walker Award]] winner and Heisman runner-up [[Toby Gerhart]] into a star during that time. The younger Harbaugh also gave Taggart responsibility for recruiting in Taggart's home state of [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kentucky]], and [[Riverside County, California]].<ref name=Announcement/>{{Dead link|date=December 2019}}\n\n=== Western Kentucky (2010\u20132012) ===\nIn 2010, Taggart left his position at Stanford as the running backs coach in order to become the head football coach of his alma-mater, Western Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/sunbelt/2009-11-23-western-kentucky-taggart_N.htm|title=Western Kentucky hires Stanford assistant Willie Taggart as coach \u2013 USATODAY.com|last=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 23, 2009|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> In their first year under Taggart, the Hilltoppers broke a 26-game losing streak while finishing the season with a record of 2\u201310.\n\nIn 2011, Taggart led WKU to a 7\u20135 season, where the Hilltoppers lost the first 4 games of the season, but then won 7 of their last 8 games. Although having a winning record, they were not invited to a bowl game that year. In 2012, Taggart led WKU once again to a bowl-eligible record of 7\u20135. The Hilltoppers accepted an invitation to play [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] in the [[2012 Little Caesars Pizza Bowl|Little Caesars]] Bowl on December 26, 2012, on [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbko.com/sports/headlines/WKU-Football-Accepts-Invitation-To-Little-Caesars-Pizza-Bowl-WillFace-Central-Michigan--181779501.html?ref=501|title=WKU Football Accepts Invitation To Little Caesars Pizza Bowl, WillFace Central Michigan|date=December 2, 2012|website=[[WBKO]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=December 2019}} However, Taggart did not coach in this bowl game having already accepted the head coaching position of the South Florida Bulls on December 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gousfbulls.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=7700&ATCLID=205822229|title=Welcome Home Willie Taggart|date=December 8, 2012|work=GoUSFBulls.com|publisher=[[South Florida Bulls]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== South Florida (2013\u20132016) ===\n\nOn December 7, 2012, Taggart took over as head coach at the University of South Florida in his native [[Tampa Bay]] area.\n\nIn his first season, Taggart led the Bulls to a 2\u201310 season. The following season, Taggart's team doubled the number of wins and finished with a 4\u20138 record. During the off-season, Taggart made several personnel changes, including replacing the offensive and defensive coordinators. The change of schemes as well as the development of his first two recruiting classes provided the team with much needed energy and depth of positions.\n\nIn 2015, led by conference leaders quarterback [[Quinton Flowers]] and running back [[Marlon Mack]], the Bulls started the season 1\u20133 before finishing the regular season with a record of 8\u20135 and earning bowl eligibility for the first time in five years. The Bulls lost to WKU in the [[Miami Beach Bowl]].\n\nIn 2016, the Bulls went 10\u20132 and won a share of the [[American Athletic Conference|AAC]] East division. This was the Bulls first double digit win season in school history.\n\n===Oregon (2017)===\nOn December 7, 2016, the University of Oregon announced Taggart as the Ducks' new head coach, replacing the fired [[Mark Helfrich (American football)|Mark Helfrich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goducks.com/news/2016/12/7/taggart-named-head-football-coach.aspx|title=Taggart Named Head Football Coach|last=Moseley|first=Rob|date=December 7, 2016|website=GoDucks.com|publisher=[[Oregon Ducks]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, three Oregon football players were hospitalized after grueling military-style workouts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18491292/three-oregon-ducks-football-players-hospitalized-strength-conditioning-workouts|title=Report: 3 Oregon football players hospitalized after 'grueling' workouts|last=Jennings|first=Chantel|date=January 17, 2017|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[ESPN Inc.]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> Multiple sources described the workouts to the Oregonian as \"akin to military basic training, with one said to include up to an hour of continuous push-ups and up-downs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtsp.com/sports/oregon-takes-action-after-football-players-hospitalized/387071783|title=Oregon takes action after football players hospitalized|date=January 18, 2017|website=[[WTSP]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> Taggart personally visited the ill and hospitalized players to wish them a speedy recovery. \"I have visited with the three young men involved in the incidents in the past few days and I have been in constant contact with their families, offering my sincere apologies,\u201d Taggart said in the statement. \u201cAs the head football coach, I hold myself responsible for all of our football-related activities and the safety of our students must come first. I have addressed the issue with our strength and conditioning staff, and I fully support the actions taken today by the university. I want to thank our medical staff and doctors for caring for all of our young men, and I want to apologize to the university, our students, alumni and fans.\u201d\n\nTaggart's hiring at Oregon drew attention to the low number of African American head coaches in major college football (14 out of 128 schools). The hiring came several years after Oregon\u2019s passing of House Bill 3118, which requires state-funded schools to interview qualified minority candidates for top coaching and athletic administration positions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/oregon-law-on-hiring-practices-might-be-just-what-college-football-needs/2016/12/08/866396de-bd91-11e6-94ac-3d324840106c_story.html|title=Oregon law could be college football\u2019s version of the \u2018Rooney Rule\u2019|author=Kilgore|first=Adam|date=December 9, 2016|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOregon went 7-5 overall and 4-5 in the Pac-12 in 2017 with Taggart at the reins. The Ducks beat Nebraska, Arizona and rival Oregon State. They were bested by UCLA, Stanford and Washington. Additionally, the Ducks lost The Las Vegas Bowl to Boise State on December 16 with [[Mario Cristobal]] at the helm after Taggart accepted the position at Florida State.\n\n=== Florida State (2018\u20132019) ===\nOn December 5, 2017, Taggart accepted the head coaching job at [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], replacing [[Jimbo Fisher]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2017/12/5/16733506/willie-taggart-florida-state-head-coach-who-is|title=Meet Willie Taggart, Florida State\u2019s next head coach|last=Godfrey|first=Steven|date=December 5, 2017|work=[[SB Nation]]|access-date=December 5, 2017|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|last2=Moriarty|first2=Morgan}}</ref> In his first season, the Seminoles finished 5-7, their first losing season since 1976, [[Bobby Bowden]]'s first year, if you dont count the NCAA sanctions from the 2006 season. They were not invited to a bowl for the first time since the end of the 1981 season, breaking the longest active bowl appearance streak in [[FBS programs|FBS]], if you don't count the forfeited bowl appearances by NCAA sanctions. Florida State fans were not used to staying home for bowl season, and there were numerous calls for Taggart's firing. However, school president [[John Thrasher]] and athletic director Dave Coburn voiced confidence in Taggart. According to a story in ''[[Bleacher Report]],'' Florida State had bottomed out in 2018 due in part to cultural problems dating from Fisher's tenure. In particular, Taggart was stunned at the casual approach to academics that prevailed at the time of his arrival. Under Fisher's tenure, FSU's [[Academic Progress Rate]] (APR) was the worst in FBS, further complicating Taggart's efforts to rebuild the program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2841875-the-mess-jimbo-left-inside-fsus-fall-and-willie-taggarts-plan-to-rise-again|title=The Mess Jimbo Left: Inside FSU's Fall and Willie Taggart's Plan to Rise Again|author1=Hayes|first=Matt|date=June 24, 2019|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|publisher=[[WarnerMedia]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> A <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/acc/2019/05/10/florida-state-football-apr-last-among-power-five-schools/1163870001/|title=Florida State football finishes last in APR among Power Five schools|author1=McGahee III|first=Wayne|date=May 10, 2019|website=[[Tallahassee Democrat]]|publisher=[[Gannett]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> Following a 4-5 start to the 2019 season, Taggart was fired during mid-season in November 2019.For the removal of Taggart, Florida State had to pay over $20M in buyouts, including about $18M to Taggart after the firing and over $4M paid to Oregon at his hiring ($3M to end Taggart's contract with Oregon and additional $1.3M Oregon still owe South Florida for hiring Taggart away).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2019/11/florida-state-willie-taggart-buyout|title=Florida State will end up paying 3 buyouts, totaling over $20 million, to fire Willie Taggart|last=Scott|first=Nate|date=November 4, 2019|website=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Florida Atlantic University (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn December 11, 2019, two days after Lane Kiffin resigned from FAU and accepted the head coach position at [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], FAU announced the hiring of Taggart as the school's next head coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28276883/willie-taggart-lands-fau-following-fsu-firing|title=FAU turns to Taggart to replace Kiffin as coach|date=2019-12-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The 5-year contract would pay Taggart $750,000 annually with a $3M buyout if Taggart leaves before December 1, 2022.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nTaggart and his wife Taneshia have three children: two sons (Willie Jr. and Jackson) and a daughter (Morgan).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gousfbulls.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=7700&ATCLID=205822984|title=Willie Taggart Bio|website=GoUSFBulls.com|publisher=[[South Florida Bulls]]|url-status=dead|access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = both }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky Hilltoppers]]\n | conf      = [[Sun Belt Conference]]\n | startyear = 2010\n | endyear   = 2012\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]]\n | name         = [[2010 WKU Hilltoppers football team|Western Kentucky]]\n | overall      = 2\u201310\n | conference   = 2\u20136\n | confstanding = 9th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl  