{"title_page": "Human nose", "text_new": "{{other uses|Nose (disambiguation)}}\n{{about|noses in humans|the article about noses in general|nose}}\n\n{{Infobox anatomy\n| Name        = Human nose\n| Latin       = nasus\n| Greek       = \n| Image       = Fort Ross Elena wearing Traditional Russian Costume (cropped).jpg\n| Caption     = View of human nose\n| Width       = 240\n| Image2      = Head Olfactory Nerve Labeled.png\n| Caption2    = Cross-section of the interior of a nose showing parts involved in smell ([[olfactory system|olfaction]])\n| Precursor   = \n| System      = \n| Artery      = [[sphenopalatine artery]], [[greater palatine artery]]\n| Vein        = [[facial vein]]\n| Nerve       = [[external nasal nerve]]\n| Lymph       = \n}}\nThe '''human nose''' is the most protruding part of the [[face]].  It bears the [[nostril]]s and is the first organ of the [[respiratory system]].  It is also the principal organ in the [[olfactory system]].  The shape of the [[nose]] is determined by the [[nasal bone]]s and the [[nasal cartilages]], including the [[nasal septum]] which separates the nostrils and divides the [[nasal cavity]] into two. On average the nose of a [[male]] is larger than that of a [[female]].\n\nThe main function of the nose is [[breathing]], and the [[nasal mucosa]] lining the nasal cavity and the [[paranasal sinuses]] carries out the necessary conditioning of inhaled air by warming and moistening it. [[Nasal concha]]e, [[Conch|shell-like]] bones in the walls of the cavities, play a major part in this process. Filtering of the air by [[nasal hair]] in the nostrils prevents large particles from entering the lungs. [[Sneezing]] is a [[reflex]] to expel unwanted particles from the nose that irritate the mucosal lining. Sneezing can [[Transmission (medicine)|transmit infections]], because [[aerosol]]s are created in which the [[Respiratory droplets|droplets]] can harbour [[pathogen]]s.\n\nAnother major function of the nose is [[olfaction]], the sense of smell. The area of [[olfactory epithelium]], in the upper nasal cavity, contains specialised [[olfactory cells]] responsible for this function.\n\nThe nose is also involved in the function of speech. [[Nasal vowel]]s and [[nasal consonant]]s are produced in the process of [[nasalisation]]. The hollow cavities of the paranasal sinuses act as sound chambers that modify and amplify speech and other vocal sounds.\n\nThere are many [[plastic surgery]] procedures on the nose, known as [[Rhinoplasty|rhinoplasties]] available to correct various structural defects or to change the shape of the nose. Defects may be [[Birth defect|congenital]], or result from nasal disorders or from trauma. These procedures are a type of [[plastic surgery#Reconstructive surgery|reconstructive surgery]]. [[Elective surgery|Elective procedures]] to change a nose shape are a type of [[plastic surgery#Cosmetic surgery procedures|cosmetic surgery]].\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Structure==\nSeveral [[bone]]s and [[cartilage]]s make up the bony-cartilaginous framework of the nose, and the internal structure.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The nose is also made up of types of [[soft tissue]] such as [[skin]], [[epithelium|epithelia]], [[mucous membrane]], [[muscle]]s, [[nerve]]s, and [[blood vessel]]s. In the skin there are [[sebaceous gland]]s, and in the mucous membrane there are [[nasal glands]].<ref name=\"Singh\" /> The bones and cartilages provide strong protection for the internal structures of the nose. There are several muscles that are involved in movements of the nose. The arrangement of the cartilages allows flexibility through muscle control to enable airflow to be modified.<ref name=\"Singh\" />\n\n===Bones===\n[[File:714 Bone of Nasal Cavity.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Bones of the nose and septal cartilage]]\n[[File: Sobo 1909 100.png|thumb|Roof of the mouth showing position of palatine bones making up the floor of the nose, and forming the [[posterior nasal spine]] for the attachment of the [[musculus uvulae]].]]\nThe bony structure of the nose is provided by the [[maxilla]], [[frontal bone]], and a number of smaller bones.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\">{{cite book |last1=Standring |first1=Susan |title=Gray's anatomy : the anatomical basis of clinical practice |date=2016 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9780702052309 |pages=556\u2013565 |edition=Forty-first}}</ref>\n\n<!-- From top to bottom -->The topmost bony part of the nose is formed by the nasal part of the frontal bone, which lies between the brow ridges,<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> and ends in a serrated [[nasal notch]].<ref name=\"Gray's E-Book\">{{cite book |last1=Standring |first1=Susan |title=Gray's Anatomy E-Book: The Anatomical Basis of Clinical Practice |url=https://books.google.com/?id=b7FVCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA479&lpg=PA479&dq=nasal+notch#v=onepage&q=nasal%20notch&f=false |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |language=en |date=7 August 2015|isbn=9780702068515 }}</ref> A left and a right [[nasal bone]] join with the nasal part of the frontal bone at either side; and these at the side with the small [[lacrimal bone]]s and the [[Frontal process of maxilla|frontal process of each maxilla]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The internal roof of the nasal cavity is composed of the horizontal, perforated [[cribriform plate]] of the [[ethmoid bone]] through which pass [[Axon#Sensory|sensory fibres]] of the [[olfactory nerve]]. Below and behind the cribriform plate, sloping down at an angle, is the face of the [[sphenoid bone]].\n\nThe wall separating the two cavities of the nose, the [[nasal septum]], is made up of bone inside and cartilage closer to the tip of the nose.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The bony part is formed by the [[Perpendicular plate of ethmoid bone|perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone]] at the top, and the [[vomer|vomer bone]] below.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The floor of the nose is made up of the [[incisive bone]] and the [[Horizontal plate of palatine bone|horizontal plates of the palatine bones]], and this makes up the [[hard palate]] of the roof of the mouth. The two horizontal plates join together at the midline and form the [[posterior nasal spine]] that gives attachment to the [[musculus uvulae]] in the [[uvula]].\n\nThe two maxilla bones join at the base of the nose at the lower nasal midline between the nostrils, and at the top of the [[philtrum]] to form the [[anterior nasal spine]]. This thin projection of bone holds the cartilaginous center of the nose.<ref name=\"Knipe\">{{cite web |last1=Knipe |first1=Henry |title=Anterior nasal spine fracture {{!}} Radiology Case {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/cases/anterior-nasal-spine-fracture |website=radiopaedia.org |accessdate=24 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeologyinfo.com/archaeology-evolution-glossary-n/|title=Glossary: nasal spine (anterior)|publisher=ArchaeologyInfo.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301183829/http://archaeologyinfo.com/archaeology-evolution-glossary-n/|archive-date=2017-03-01|url-status=live|accessdate=2017-02-28}}</ref> It is also an important [[Cephalometric analysis#Cephalometric landmarks|cephalometric landmark]].<ref>Dory, Miri (March 13, 2014). [http://www.cephx.com/cephalometric-analysis/ \"Cephalometric analysis\"], Cephx.</ref>\n\n===Cartilages===\n[[File:Gray852.png|thumb|upright=0.6|left|Nasal cartilages]]\nThe [[nasal cartilages]] are the [[septal nasal cartilage|septal]], [[lateral nasal cartilage|lateral]], [[major alar cartilage|major alar]], and [[minor alar cartilage|minor alar]] cartilages.<ref name=\"Lang\">{{cite book |last1=Lang |first1=Johannes |title=Clinical Anatomy of the Nose, Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses |url=https://books.google.com/?id=afNfhoxkDeoC&pg=PA10&dq=nasal+cartilages#v=onepage&q=nasal%20cartilages&f=false |publisher=Thieme |language=en |date=1989|isbn=9783137384014 }}</ref> The major and minor cartilages are also known as the greater and lesser alar cartilages. There is a narrow strip of cartilage called the [[vomeronasal cartilage]] that lies between the [[vomer]] and the septal cartilage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vomeronasal cartilage |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/medical/vomeronasal%20cartilage}}</ref>\n\nThe [[septal nasal cartilage]], extends from the nasal bones in the midline, to the bony part of the [[nasal septum|septum]] in the midline, posteriorly. It then passes along the floor of the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Schunke\">{{cite book |last1=Sch\u00fcnke |first1=Michael |last2=Ross |first2=Lawrence M. |last3=Schulte |first3=Erik |last4=Lamperti |first4=Edward D. |last5=Schumacher |first5=Udo |title=Thieme Atlas of Anatomy: Head and Neuroanatomy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wlGDPwz_7KoC&pg=PA18&dq=Lateral+nasal+cartilage#v=onepage&q=Lateral%20nasal%20cartilage&f=false |publisher=Thieme |language=en |date=2007|isbn=9781588904416 }}</ref> The septum is quadrangular\u2013the upper half is attached to the two [[lateral nasal cartilages]] which are fused to the dorsal septum in the midline. The septum is laterally attached, with loose ligaments, to the bony margin of the [[anterior nasal aperture]], while the inferior ends of the lateral cartilages are free (unattached). The three or four [[minor alar cartilage]]s are adjacent to the lateral cartilages, held in the [[connective tissue]] membrane, that connects the lateral cartilages to the frontal process of the maxilla.\n\nThe nasal bones in the upper part of the nose are joined together by the midline [[nasal bone|internasal suture]]. They join with the [[Septal nasal cartilage|septal cartilage]] at a junction known as the '''rhinion'''. The rhinion is the midpoint of the internasal suture at the join with the cartilage, and from the rhinion to the apex, or tip, the framework is of cartilage.\n\nThe [[major alar cartilage]]s are thin, U-shaped plates of cartilage on each side of the nose that form the lateral and medial walls of the vestibule, known as the medial and lateral crura. The medial crura are attached to the septal cartilage, forming fleshy parts at the front of the nostrils on each side of the septum, called the ''medial crural footpods''. The medial crura meet at the midline below the end of the septum to form the '''columella'''<ref name=\"Bell\">{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Daniel J. |title=Columella {{!}} Radiology Reference Article {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/articles/columella |website=Radiopaedia}}</ref> and '''lobule'''. The lobule contains the tip of the nose and its base contains the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> At the peaks of the folds of the medial crura, they form the '''alar domes''' the tip-defining points of the nose, separated by a notch.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> They then fold outwards, above and to the side of the nostrils forming the lateral crura.<ref name=\"Ballenger\" /><ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book |last1=Singh |first1=Vishram |title=Textbook of anatomy head, neck and brain. Volume 3 |date=2014 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9788131237274 |pages=251\u2013263 |edition=Second}}</ref> The major alar cartilages are freely moveable and can respond to muscles to either open or constrict the nostrils.<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Keith |last2=Dalley |first2=Arthur |last3=Agur |first3=Anne |title=Clinically oriented anatomy |date=2018 |publisher=Wolters Kluwer |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=963\u2013973 |edition=Eighth}}</ref>\n\nThere is a reinforcing structure known as the '''nasal scroll''' that resists internal collapse from airflow pressure generated by normal breathing. This structure is formed by the junction between the lateral and major cartilages. Their edges interlock by one scrolling upwards and one scrolling inwards.<ref name=\"Ballenger\">{{cite book |last1=Ballenger |first1=John Jacob |last2=Snow |first2=James Byron |title=Ballenger's Otorhinolaryngology: Head and Neck Surgery |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BastAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA643&lpg=PA643&dq=nasal+scroll#v=onepage&q=nasal%20scroll&f=false |publisher=PMPH-USA |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en |date=2003|isbn=9781550091977 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gubisch\">{{cite book |last1=Gubisch |first1=Wolfgang |title=Mastering Advanced Rhinoplasty |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KR4-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&dq=nasal+scroll#v=onepage&q=nasal%20scroll&f=false |publisher=Springer |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en |date=10 November 2017|isbn=9783319675374 }}</ref>\n\n===Muscles===\nThe muscles of the nose are a subgroup of the [[muscles of facial expression]]. They are involved in respiration and facial expression. The muscles of the nose include the procerus, nasalis, depressor septi nasalis, levator labii superioris alaeque nasalis, and the orbicularis oris of the mouth. As are all of the facial muscles, the muscles of the nose are innervated by the facial nerve and its branches.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Although each muscle is independent, the muscles of the nose form a continuous layer with connections between all the components of the muscles and ligaments, in the nasal part of a [[superficial muscular aponeurotic system]] (SMAS).<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"  /><ref name=\"Saban\">{{cite journal |last1=Saban |first1=Y |last2=Andretto Amodeo |first2=C |last3=Hammou |first3=JC |last4=Polselli |first4=R |title=An anatomical study of the nasal superficial musculoaponeurotic system: surgical applications in rhinoplasty. |journal=Archives of Facial Plastic Surgery |date=2009 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=109\u201315 |doi=10.1001/archfaci.10.2.109 |pmid=18347238}}</ref> The SMAS is continuous from the nasofrontal process to the nasal tip. It divides at level of the nasal valve  into superficial and deep layers, each layer having medial and lateral components.<ref name=\"Saban\" />\n\nThe [[procerus muscle]] produces wrinkling over the bridge of the nose, and is active in concentration and frowning. It is a prime target for [[Botulinum toxin#Cosmetics|Botox procedures]] in the forehead to remove the lines between the eyes.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[nasalis muscle]] consists of two main parts: a transverse part called the [[compressor naris]], and an alar part termed the [[dilator naris muscle|dilator naris]].  The compressor naris muscle compresses the nostrils and may completely close them. The alar part, the dilator naris mainly consists of the dilator naris posterior, and a much smaller dilator naris anterior, and this muscle flares the nostrils. The dilator naris helps to form the upper ridge of the philtrum.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The anterior, and the posterior dilator naris, (the alar part of the nasalis muscle), give support to the nasal valves.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[Depressor septi nasi muscle|depressor septi muscle]] may sometimes be absent or rudimentary.  The depressor septi pulls the columella, the septum, and the tip of the nose downwards. At the start of inspiration this muscle tenses the nasal septum and with the dilator naris widens the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[levator labii superioris alaeque nasi]],  divides into a medial and a lateral slip. The medial slip blends into the perichondrium of the major alar cartilage and its overlying skin. The lateral slip blends at the side of the upper lip with the [[levator labii superioris]], and with the [[orbicularis oris]].  The lateral slip raises the upper lip and deepens  and increases the curve above the nasolabial furrow. The medial slip pulls the lateral crus upwards and modifies the curve of the furrow around the alae, and dilates the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Soft tissue===\n\nThe skin of the nose varies in thickness along its length.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> From the glabella to the bridge (the nasofrontal angle) the skin is thick, fairly flexible, and mobile. It tapers to the bridge where it is thinnest and least flexible as it is closest to the underlying bone.  From the bridge until the tip of the nose the skin is thin. The tip is covered in skin that is as thick as the top section, and has many large sebaceous glands.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name= \"Moore\" />\nThe thickness of the skin varies but is still separated from the underlying bones and cartilage by four layers \u2013 a superficial  [[panniculus adiposus|fatty layer]]; a [[connective tissue#Types|fibromuscular layer]] continued from the [[Superficial muscular aponeurotic system|SMAS]]; a deep fatty layer, and the [[periosteum]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nOther areas of [[soft tissue]] are found where there is no support from cartilage - these include an area around the sides of the septum - the paraseptal area; an area around the lateral cartliages; an area at the top of the nostril, and an area in the alae.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===External nose===\n\nThe nasal root is the top of the nose that attaches the nose to the [[forehead]].<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The nasal root is above the [[nasal bridge|bridge]] and below the [[glabella]], forming an indentation known as the [[nasion]] at the frontonasal suture where the [[frontal bone]] meets the nasal bones.<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite web |title=Nasion definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary |url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/nasion |website=www.collinsdictionary.com |accessdate=2019-11-06 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe '''nasal dorsum''' also known as the ''nasal ridge'' is the border between the root and the tip of the nose which in profile can be variously shaped.<ref name=\"TortAnag\">{{cite book |last1=Tortora |first1=G |last2=Anagnostakos |first2=N |title=Principles of anatomy and physiology |url=https://archive.org/details/principlesofan1987tort |url-access=registration |date=1987 |publisher=Harper & Row |isbn=978-0063507296 |page=[https://archive.org/details/principlesofan1987tort/page/556 556] |edition=5th. Harper international}}</ref>\n\nThe '''ala of the nose''' (ala nasi, wing of the nose) is the lower lateral surface of the external nose, shaped by the alar cartilage and covered in dense connective tissue.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The alae flare out to form a rounded eminence around the [[nostril]].<ref name=\"TortAnag\" />\n\n[[Sexual dimorphism]] is evident in the larger nose of the male. This is due to the increased [[testosterone]] that thickens the [[brow ridge]] and the bridge of the nose making it wider.<ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unl.edu/rhames/courses/male_facial_beauty.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130021737/http://www.unl.edu/rhames/courses/male_facial_beauty.htm |archivedate=2007-11-30 }}</ref>\n\n===Nasal cavity===\n{{Main|Nasal cavity}}\n[[File:Anatomy of the human nasal cavity.png|thumb|Anatomy of the nasal cavity. [[Nasal-associated lymphoid tissue]] labelled NALT|alt=]]\nThe [[nasal cavity]] is the large internal space of the nose, and is in two parts \u2013 the [[Nasal cavity#Structure|nasal vestibule]] and the nasal cavity proper.<ref name=\"Singh\" /> The nasal vestibule is the frontmost part of the [[nasal cavity]], enclosed by cartilages.  The vestibule is lined with skin, hair follicles, and a large number of sebaceous glands.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /><ref name=\"Singh\" /> A mucous ridge known as the '''limen nasi''' separates the vestibule from the rest of the nasal cavity and marks the change from the skin of the vestibule to the [[respiratory epithelium]] of the rest of the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Singh\" /> This area is also known as a [[mucocutaneous junction]] and has a dense [[microvasculature]]. <ref name=\"Wolfram-Gabel\">{{cite journal |last1=Wolfram-Gabel |first1=R |last2=Sick |first2=H |title=Microvascularization of the mucocutaneous junction of the nose. |journal=Surgical and Radiologic Anatomy |date=February 2002 |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |pmid=12197007|doi=10.1007/s00276-002-0009-6 }}</ref>\n\nThe nasal cavity is divided into two cavities by the nasal septum, and each is accessed by an external nostril.<ref name=\"Moore\" /><ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The division into two cavities enables the functioning of the [[Nasal cycle#Benefits in breathing|nasal cycle]] that slows down the conditioning process of the inhaled air.<ref name=\"Hummel\">{{citation|author1=Thomas Hummel|author2=Antje Welge-L\u00fcssen|title=Taste and Smell: An Update|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fuxS-p6bpuwC&pg=PA12|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-8055-8123-3|pages=12\u2013}}</ref>\nAt the back of the nasal cavity there are two openings, called [[choana]]e (also ''posterior nostrils''), that give entrance to the [[nasopharynx]], and rest of the [[respiratory tract]].<ref name=\"anatomy\" />\n\nOn the outer wall of each cavity are three shell-like bones called [[nasal concha|conchae]], arranged as [[superior nasal concha|superior]], [[middle nasal concha|middle]] and [[inferior nasal concha]]e. Below each concha is a corresponding superior, middle, and inferior [[nasal meatus]], or passage.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> Sometimes when the superior concha is narrow, a fourth supreme nasal concha is present situated above and sharing the space with the superior concha.<ref name=\"Navarro\">{{cite book |last1=Navarro |first1=Joao A. C. |title=The Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: Surgical Anatomy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=dJnvCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=supreme+nasal+concha#v=onepage&q=supreme%20nasal%20concha&f=false |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en |date=6 December 2012|isbn=9783642568299 }}</ref> The term concha refers to the actual bone - when covered by soft tissue and mucosa, and functioning, a concha is termed a '''turbinate'''.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nMost of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is lined with [[respiratory epithelium]] as [[nasal mucosa]]. In the roof of each cavity is an area of specialised [[olfactory epithelium]]. This region is about 5 square cm, covering the superior concha, the cribriform plate, and the nasal septum.<ref name=\"McGraw\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=Kenneth |title=Anatomy & physiology : the unity of form and function |date=2012 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=978-0073378251 |pages=593\u2013595 |edition=6th}}</ref>\n\nThere is a '''nasal valve''' area that is the narrowest part of the nasal passage. An external valve exists in the larger ala part of the vestibule. An internal nasal valve typically referred to as the nasal valve, is a slit-like segment between part of the upper lateral cartilage and the septum in the middle third of the cavity.<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite journal |last1=Becker |first1=DG |last2=Becker |first2=SS |title=Treatment of nasal obstruction from nasal valve collapse with alar batten grafts. |journal=Journal of Long-Term Effects of Medical Implants |date=2003 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=259\u201369 |pmid=14516189|doi=10.1615/JLongTermEffMedImplants.v13.i3.100 }}</ref><ref name=\"Pecorari\">{{cite journal |last1=Pecorari |first1=G |last2=Riva |first2=G |last3=Bianchi |first3=FA |last4=Cavallo |first4=G |last5=Revello |first5=F |last6=Bironzo |first6=M |last7=Verz\u00e8 |first7=L |last8=Garzaro |first8=M |last9=Ramieri |first9=G |title=The effect of closed septorhinoplasty on nasal functions and on external and internal nasal valves: A prospective study. |journal=American Journal of Rhinology & Allergy |date=1 September 2017 |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=323\u2013327 |doi=10.2500/ajra.2017.31.4459 |pmid=28859710}}</ref> The valves regulate the airflow and resistance. Air breathed in is forced to pass through the narrow internal nasal valve, and then expands as it moves into the nasal cavity. The sudden change in the speed and pressure of the airflow creates turbulence that allows optimum contact with the respiratory epithelium for the necessary warming, moisturising, and filtering. The turbulence also allows movement of the air to pass over the olfactory epithelium and transfer odor information.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"/> The angle of the valve between the septum and the sidewall needs to be sufficient for unobstructed airflow,<ref name=\"Fischer\">{{cite journal |last1=Fischer |first1=H |last2=Gubisch |first2=W |title=Nasal valves--importance and surgical procedures. |journal=Facial Plastic Surgery |date=November 2006 |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=266\u201380 |doi=10.1055/s-2006-954845 |pmid=17131269|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5347f92dbb17b43df59832f5c5c311f0cf733b48 }}</ref> and this is normally between 10 and 15 degrees.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"/>\n\nThe borders of each nasal cavity are a roof, floor, medial wall (the septum), and lateral wall.<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The middle part of the roof of the nasal cavity is composed of the horizontal, perforated [[cribriform plate]] of the [[ethmoid bone]], through which pass [[Axon#Sensory|sensory fibres]] of the [[olfactory nerve]] into the cranial cavity.<ref name=\"Singh\" />\n\n====Paranasal sinuses====\n{{Main|Paranasal sinuses}}\n[[File:724 Paranasal Sinuses.jpg|thumb|Paranasal sinuses]]\nThe [[respiratory epithelium|mucosa]] that lines the nasal cavity extends into its chambers, the [[paranasal sinuses]].<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The nasal cavity and the paranasal sinuses are referred to as the ''sinonasal tract'' or ''sinonasal region'', and its anatomy is recognised as being unique and complex.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis JS |first1=Jr |title=Sinonasal Squamous Cell Carcinoma: A Review with Emphasis on Emerging Histologic Subtypes and the Role of Human Papillomavirus. |journal=Head and Neck Pathology |date=March 2016 |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=60\u201367 |doi=10.1007/s12105-016-0692-y |pmid=26830402|pmc=4746138 }}</ref><ref name=\"HandN\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis |first1=J |title=The sinonasal tract: another potential \"hot spot\" for carcinomas with transcriptionally-active human papillomavirus. |journal=Head and Neck Pathology |date=2014 |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=241\u20139 |doi=10.1007/s12105-013-0514-4 |pmid=24338611|pmc=4126925 }}</ref>\n\nFour paired paranasal sinuses drain into regions of the nasal cavity.\nThe sinuses are air-filled extensions of the nasal cavity into the cranial bones.<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The frontal sinuses are located in the frontal bone; the sphenoidal sinuses in the sphenoid bone; the maxillary sinuses in the maxilla; and the ethmoidal sinuses in the ethmoid bone.<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nA narrow opening called a [[sinus ostium]] from each of the paranasal sinuses allows drainage into the nasal cavity. The maxillary sinus is the largest of the sinuses and drains into the middle meatus. Most of the ostia open into the middle meatus and the anterior ethmoid, that together are termed the [[Nasal cavity#Structure|ostiomeatal complex]].<ref name=\"Wagenmann\">{{cite journal |last1=Wagenmann |first1=M |last2=Naclerio |first2=RM |title=Anatomic and physiologic considerations in sinusitis. |journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology |date=September 1992 |volume=90 |issue=3 Pt 2 |pages=419\u201323 |doi=10.1016/0091-6749(92)90161-t |pmid=1527330}}</ref> Adults have a high concentration of cilia in the ostia.The cilia in the sinuses beat towards the openings into the nasal cavity. The increased cilia and the narrowness of the sinus openings allow for an increased time for moisturising, and warming.<ref name=\"Wagenmann\" />\n\nExcessive moisture as tears collected in the [[lacrimal sac]] travel down the [[nasolacrimal duct]]s where they drain into the inferior meatus in the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Saladin\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=K |title=Human anatomy |date=2011 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780071222075 |page=480 |edition=3rd}}</ref>\n\n===Nose shape===\nThe shape of the nose varies widely due to differences in the nasal bone shapes and formation of the bridge of the nose. Some nose shapes were classified for [[rhinoplasty|surgeries]] by Eden Warwick in ''Nasology'' 1848:\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Class_I_nose.jpg| Class I. The [[aquiline nose]]. \nFile:Class_II_nose.jpg| Class II. The Grecian nose. \nFile:Class_III_nose.jpg| Class III. The African nose. \nFile:Class_IV_nose.jpg| Class IV. The hawk nose. \nFile:Class_V_nose.jpg| Class V. The snub nose. \nFile:Class_VI_nose.jpg| Class VI. The celestial nose. \n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Topinard nasal index.png|thumb|Nose shapes used in [[Paul Topinard|Topinard's]] nasal index]]\n[[Paul Topinard]] developed the [[Herbert Hope Risley#Ethnographic Survey of Bengal:1885-91|nasal index]] as a method of classifying ethnic groups. The index is based on the ratio of the breadth of the nose to its height.<ref name=\"Leong\">{{cite journal |last1=Leong |first1=SC |last2=Eccles |first2=R |title=A systematic review of the nasal index and the significance of the shape and size of the nose in rhinology. |journal=Clinical Otolaryngology |date=June 2009 |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=191\u20138 |doi=10.1111/j.1749-4486.2009.01905.x |pmid=19531167}}</ref> The nasal dimensions are also used to classify nasal morphology into five types: ''Hyperleptorrhine'' is a very long, narrow nose with a nasal index of 40 to 55.<ref name=\"Index\"/> ''Leptorrhine'' describes a long, narrow nose with an index of 55\u201370.<ref name=\"Index\"/> ''Mesorrhine'' is a medium nose with an index of 70\u201385. ''Platyrrhine'' is a short, broad nose with an index of 85\u201399\u00b79. The fifth type is the ''hyperplatyrrhine'' having an index of more than 100.<ref name=\"Index\">{{cite web |title=Anthropometric_evaluation_of_nasal_height_nasal_breadth_and_nasal_index_among_Bini_children_In_Southern_Nigeria |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/332912694 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome deformities of the nose are named, such as the '''pug nose''' and the [[saddle nose]]. The pug nose is characterised by excess tissue from the apex that is out of proportion to the rest of the nose. A low and underdeveloped nasal bridge may also be evident.<ref name=\"Roe\">{{cite journal |last1=Roe |first1=J. O. |title=The Deformity Termed 'Pug Nose' and Its Correction by a Simple Operation |issue=2 |journal=Archives of Otolaryngology\u2013Head & Neck Surgery |volume=115 |pages=156\u2013157 |language=en |doi=10.1001/archotol.1989.01860260030010 |pmid=2643972 |date=1 February 1989}}</ref> A saddle nose is mostly associated with trauma to the nose but can be caused by other conditions including [[leprosy]].<ref name=\"Coordes\">{{cite journal |last1=Coordes |first1=A |last2=Loose |first2=SM |last3=Hofmann |first3=VM |last4=Hamilton GS |first4=3rd |last5=Riedel |first5=F |last6=Menger |first6=DJ |last7=Albers |first7=AE |title=Saddle nose deformity and septal perforation in granulomatosis with polyangiitis. |journal=Clinical Otolaryngology |date=February 2018 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=291\u2013299 |doi=10.1111/coa.12977 |pmid=28881107}}</ref>\n\n[[Werner syndrome]], a condition that causes the appearance of premature aging, causes a \"bird-like\" appearance due to pinching of the nose.<ref name=\"Leis\">{{cite book |vauthors=Oshima J, Martin GM, Hisama FM |veditors=Adam MP, Ardinger HH, Pagon RA|display-editors=etal |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1514/ |title=Werner Syndrome |date=2002-12-02 |orig-year=Updated 2016-09-29 |work=GeneReviews\u00ae |location=Seattle, WA |publisher=University of Washington |via=NCBI |accessdate=2017-08-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118125119/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1514/ |archivedate=2017-01-18 }}</ref>\n\n[[Down syndrome]] commonly presents a small nose with a flattened nasal bridge. This can be due to the absence of one or both  nasal bones, shortened nasal bones, or nasal bones that have not fused in the midline.<ref name=\"Sonek\">{{cite journal |last1=Sonek |first1=JD |last2=Cicero |first2=S |last3=Neiger |first3=R |last4=Nicolaides |first4=KH |title=Nasal bone assessment in prenatal screening for trisomy 21. |journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology |date=November 2006 |volume=195 |issue=5 |pages=1219\u201330 |doi=10.1016/j.ajog.2005.11.042 |pmid=16615922}}</ref><ref name=\"Persico\">{{cite journal |last1=Persico|display-authors=etal|first1=N |title=Nasal bone assessment in fetuses with trisomy 21 at 16-24 weeks of gestation by three-dimensional ultrasound. |journal=Prenatal Diagnosis |date=March 2012 |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=240\u20134 |doi=10.1002/pd.2938 |pmid=22430721|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/24e76ebcd06a61538da3b98dedab4b6c7e744fd7}}</ref>\n\n==Blood supply and drainage==\n===Supply===\n[[File:Blausen 0170 CarotidArteries.png|thumb|Carotid arteries]]\n[[File:Arteries of the Nose.jpg|thumb|Multiple arteries supply blood to the nose; the nasal septum, shown here is supplied by the anterior and posterior ethmoidal arteries at top; the sphenopalantine artery at the back, and the anterior ethoidal artery and the superior labial artery over the cartilage. These arteries join together at [[Kiesselbach's plexus]].|alt=]]\n\nThe blood supply to the nose is provided by branches of the [[Ophthalmic artery|ophthalmic]], [[Maxillary artery|maxillary]], and [[facial artery|facial arteries]] \u2013 branches of the [[carotid arteries]]. Branches of these arteries [[Circulatory anastomosis|anastomose]] to form [[plexus]]es in and under the nasal mucosa.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> In the septal region [[Kiesselbach's plexus]] is a common site of nosebleeds.\n\nBranches of the ophthalmic artery \u2013 the [[anterior ethmoidal artery|anterior]] and [[posterior ethmoidal artery|posterior ethmoidal arteries]] supply the roof, upper bony septum, and ethmoidal and frontal sinuses. The anterior ethmoidal artery also helps to supply the lower septal cartilage.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Another branch is the [[dorsal nasal artery]] a terminal branch that supplies the skin of the alae and dorsum.\n\nBranches of the maxillary artery include the [[greater palatine artery]]; the [[sphenopalatine artery]] and its  branches \u2013 the [[posterior lateral nasal arteries]] and [[Posterior septal branches of sphenopalatine artery|posterior septal nasal branches]]; the pharyngeal branch; and the [[infraorbital artery]] and its branches \u2013 the superior anterior and posterior alveolar arteries.\n\nThe sphenopalatine artery and the ethmoid arteries supply the outer walls of the nasal cavity. There is additional supply from a branch of the facial artery \u2013 the superior labial artery. The sphenopalantine artery is the artery primarily responsible for supplying the nasal mucosa.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe skin of the alae is supplied by the septal and [[lateral nasal branch of facial artery|lateral nasal branches of the facial artery]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The skin of the outer parts of the alae and the dorsum of the nose are supplied by the [[dorsal nasal artery]] a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and the infraorbital branch of the maxillary arteries.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Drainage===\nVeins of the nose include the [[angular vein]] that drains the side of the nose, receiving lateral nasal veins from the alae. The angular vein joins with the [[superior labial vein]]. Some small veins from the dorsum of the nose drain to the [[Frontal vein|nasal arch]] of the [[frontal vein]] at the root of the nose.\n\nIn the posterior region of the cavity, specifically in the posterior part of the inferior meatus is a [[venous plexus]] known as [[Woodruff's plexus]].<ref name=\"Solomon\">{{cite web |last1=Solomon |first1=Atyam |title=Woodruff plexus {{!}} Radiology Reference Article {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/articles/woodruff-plexus?lang=gb |website=Radiopaedia |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> This plexus is made up of large thin-walled veins with little soft tissue such as muscle or fiber. The mucosa of the plexus is thin with very few structures.<ref name=\"Chiu\">{{cite journal |last1=Chiu |first1=TW |last2=Shaw-Dunn |first2=J |last3=McGarry |first3=GW |title=Woodruff's plexus. |journal=The Journal of Laryngology and Otology |date=October 2008 |volume=122 |issue=10 |pages=1074\u20137 |doi=10.1017/S002221510800176X |pmid=18289456}}</ref>\n\n==Lymphatic drainage==\nFrom different areas of the nose superficial [[lymphatic vessel]]s run with the veins, and deep lymphatic vessels travel with the arteries.<ref name=\"Moore K\">{{cite book |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=865\u2013867|title=Clinically Oriented Anatomy|last1=Moore|first1=Keith L.|last2=Agur|first2=A. M. R.|last3=Dalley (Ii)|first3=Arthur F.|date=September 2017}}</ref>\n[[Lymph]] drains from the anterior half of the nasal cavity, including both the medial and lateral walls,<ref name=\"Singh\" /> to join that of the external nasal skin to drain into the \n[[submandibular lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The rest of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses all drain to the upper [[deep cervical lymph nodes]], either directly or through the [[retropharyngeal lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The back of the nasal floor probably drains to the [[parotid lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n==Nerve supply==\nThe nerve supply to the nose and paranasal sinuses comes from two branches of the [[trigeminal nerve]] (CN V): the [[ophthalmic nerve]] (CN V<sub>1</sub>), the [[maxillary nerve]] (CN V<sub>2</sub>), and branches from these.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nIn the nasal cavity, the nasal mucosa is divided in terms of nerve supply into a back lower part (posteroinferior), and a frontal upper part (anterosuperior). The posterior part is supplied by a branch of the maxillary nerve \u2013 the [[nasopalatine nerve]] which reaches the septum. Lateral nasal branches of the [[greater palatine nerve]] supply the lateral wall.\n<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe frontal upper part is supplied from a branch of the ophthalmic nerve \u2013 the  [[nasociliary nerve]], and its branches \u2013 the [[anterior ethmoidal nerve|anterior]] and [[posterior ethmoidal nerve]]s.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nMost of the external nose \u2013 the dorsum, and the apex are supplied by the [[infratrochlear nerve]], (a branch of the nasociliary nerve).<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name=\"Moore\"/> The external branch of the anterior ethmoidal nerve also supplies areas of skin between the root and the alae.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe alae of the nose are supplied by nasal branches of CN V<sub>2</sub>, the [[infraorbital nerve]], and [[internal nasal branches of infraorbital nerve]] that supply the septum and the vestibule.<ref name=\"Hu\">{{cite journal |last1=Hu |first1=KS |last2=Kwak |first2=J |last3=Koh |first3=KS |last4=Abe |first4=S |last5=Fontaine |first5=C |last6=Kim |first6=HJ |title=Topographic distribution area of the infraorbital nerve. |journal=Surgical and radiologic anatomy : SRA |date=July 2007 |volume=29 |issue=5 |pages=383-8 |doi=10.1007/s00276-007-0227-z |pmid=17585363}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe [[maxillary sinus]] is supplied by [[superior alveolar nerves]] from the maxillary and infraorbital nerves.<ref name=\"Moore\"/><ref name=\"Dorland's\">{{cite book |title=Dorland's illustrated medical dictionary. |publisher=Saunders/Elsevier |isbn=9781416062578 |page=1254 |edition=32nd}}</ref> The [[frontal sinus]] is supplied by branches of the [[supraorbital nerve]].<ref name=\"Moore\"/> The [[ethmoid sinus]]es are supplied by anterior and posterior ethmoid branches of the nasociliary nerve.<ref name=\"Moore\"/> The [[sphenoid sinus]] is supplied by the posterior ethmoidal nerves.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\n===Movement===\nThe muscles of the nose are supplied by branches of the [[facial nerve]]. The [[nasalis muscle]] is supplied by the [[buccal branches of the facial nerve|buccal branches]]. It may also be supplied by one of the [[zygomatic branches of the facial nerve|zygomatic branches]]. The [[procerus]] is supplied by [[temporal branches of the facial nerve]] and lower zygomatic branches; a supply from the buccal branch has also been described. The [[depressor septi]] is innervated by the buccal branch, and sometimes by the zygomatic branch, of the facial nerve. The [[levator labii superioris alaeque nasi]] is innervated by zygomatic and superior buccal branches of the facial nerve.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Smell===\nThe [[Olfaction|sense of smell]] is transmitted by the [[olfactory nerve]]s.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Olfactory nerves are bundles of very small unmyelinated axons that are derived from [[olfactory receptor neuron]]s in the [[olfactory mucosa]]. The axons are in varying stages of maturity, reflecting the constant turnover of neurons in the olfactory epithelium. A plexiform network is formed in the lamina propria, by the bundles of axons that are surrounded by olfactory ensheathing cells. In as many as twenty branches, the bundled axons cross the cribriform plate and enter the overlying olfactory bulb ending as glomeruli. Each branch is enclosed by an outer dura mater that becomes continuous with the nasal periosteum.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Autonomic supply===\nThe nasal mucosa in the nasal cavity is also supplied by the [[autonomic nervous system]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> [[Postganglionic nerve fibers]] from the [[deep petrosal nerve]] join  with [[preganglionic nerve fibers]] from the [[greater petrosal nerve]] to form the [[nerve of the pterygoid canal]].  Sympathetic postganglionic fibers are distributed to the blood vessels of the nose.  Postganglionic parasympathetic fibres derived from the pterygopalatine ganglion provide the [[secretomotor]] supply to the nasal mucous glands, and are distributed via branches of the maxillary nerves.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n==Development==\n[[Image:Gray45.png|thumb|The [[prenatal development|developing head]] at about four weeks. The olfactory pit can be seen at the top.]]\n\n===Development of the nose===\nIn the early development of the embryo, neural crest cells migrate to form the mesenchymal tissue as [[ectomesenchyme]] of the [[pharyngeal arch]]es.\u00a0 By the end of the fourth week, the first pair of pharyngeal arches form five facial prominences or processes - an unpaired [[frontonasal process]], paired mandibular processes and paired maxillary processes.<ref name=Sadler>{{Cite book|title=Langman's Medical Embryology|last=Sadler|first=T|publisher=|year=2006|isbn=9780781790697|location=|pages=280\u2013284}}</ref><ref name=Larsen>{{Cite book|title=Human Embryology|last=Larsen|first=W|publisher=|year=2001|isbn=0443065837|location=|pages=365\u2013371}}</ref>\u00a0The nose is largely formed by the fusion of these five facial prominences. The frontonasal process gives rise to the bridge of the nose. The medial nasal processes provide the crest and the tip of the nose, and the lateral nasal processes form the alae or sides of the nose. The frontonasal process is a proliferation of mesenchyme in front of\u00a0 the brain vesicles,<ref name=Sadler /> and makes up the upper border of the stomadeum.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\n\nDuring the fifth week the [[maxillary prominence|maxillary process]]es increase in size and at the same time the ectoderm of\u00a0 the frontonasal process becomes thickened at its sides and also increases in size,\u00a0 forming the nasal placodes. The nasal placodes are also known as the olfactory placodes. This development is induced by the ventral part of the forebrain.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\nIn the sixth week the ectoderm in each nasal placode invaginates to form an indented oval-shaped pit, which forms a\u00a0 surrounding\u00a0 raised ridge of tissue.<ref name=Larsen /> Each nasal pit forms a\u00a0 division between the ridges,\u00a0into a lateral nasal process on the outer edge, and a medial nasal process on the inner edge.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\n\nIn the sixth week the nasal pits deepen as they penetrate into the underlying mesenchyme.<ref name=Sadler />\u00a0At this time, the medial nasal processes migrate towards each other and fuse forming the primordium of the bridge of the nose and the septum.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0The migration is helped by the increased growth of the maxillary prominences medially, which compresses the medial nasal processes towards the midline.\u00a0 Their merging takes place at the surface, and also at a deeper level.<ref name=Sadler /> The merge forms the [[intermaxillary segment]], and this is continuous with the rostral part of the nasal septum. The tips of the maxillary processes also grow and fuse with the intermaxillary process. The intermaxillary process gives rise to the [[philtrum]] of the upper lip.<ref name=Sadler />\n\nAt the end of the sixth week the nasal pits have deepened further and they fuse to make a large ectodermal nasal sac. This sac will be above and to the back of the intermaxillary process. Leading into the seventh week, the nasal sac floor and posterior wall grow to form a thickened plate-like ectodermal structure called the nasal fin.<ref name=Larsen /> The nasal fin separates the sac from the oral cavity. Within the fin, vacuoles develop that fuse with the nasal sac. This enlarges the nasal sac and at the same time thins the fin to a membrane - the oronasal membrane that separates the nasal pits from the oral cavity.<ref name=Larsen /> During the seventh week the oronasal membrane ruptures and disintegrates to form an opening - the single primitive choana.\u00a0 The intermaxillary segment extends posteriorly to form the primary palate which makes up the floor of the nasal cavity.<ref name=Larsen /> During the eighth and ninth weeks a pair of thin extensions form from the medial walls of the maxillary process. These extensions are called the palatine shelves that form the secondary palate.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen /> The secondary palate will endochondrally ossify to form the hard palate - the end-stage floor of the nasal cavity.\u00a0 During this time ectoderm and mesoderm of the frontonasal process produce the midline septum. The septum grows down from the roof of the nasal cavity and fuses with the developing palates along the midline. The septum divides the nasal cavity into two nasal passages opening into the pharynx through the definitive choanae.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\n\nAt ten weeks, the cells differentiate into [[muscle]], [[cartilage]], and [[bone]]. Problems at this stage of development can cause [[birth defect]]s such as [[choanal atresia]] (absent or closed passage), [[facial cleft]]s and [[facial cleft|nasal dysplasia]] (faulty or incomplete development)<ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Hengerer AS, Oas RE |title=Congenital Anomalies of the Nose: Their Embryology, Diagnosis, and Management (SIPAC) |publisher=American Academy of Otolaryngology |location=Alexandria VA |year=1987 }}{{page needed|date=October 2015}}</ref> or extremely rarely polyrrhinia the formation of a duplicate nose.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polyrrhinia (Concept Id: C4274730) - MedGen - NCBI |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/medgen/894825 |website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov |language=en}}</ref>\n\nNormal [[prenatal development|development]] is critical because the newborn infant breathes through the nose for the first six weeks, and any nasal blockage will need emergency treatment to clear.<ref>{{EMedicine|article|835134|Nasal Anatomy}}</ref>\n\n===Development of the paranasal sinuses===\nThe four pairs of [[paranasal sinuses]] - the maxillary, ethmoid, sphenoid, and frontal, develop from the nasal cavity as invaginations extending into their named bones. Two pairs of sinuses form during prenatal development and two pairs form after birth. The maxillary sinuses are the first to appear during the fetal third month. They slowly expand within the maxillary bones and continue to expand throughout childhood.\u00a0The maxillary sinuses form as invaginations from the nasal sac. The ethmoid sinuses appear in the fetal fifth month as invaginations of the middle meatus. The ethmoid sinuses do not grow into the ethmoid bone and do not completely develop until puberty.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\n\nThe sphenoid sinuses are extensions of the ethmoid sinuses into the sphenoid bones. They begin to develop around two years of age, and continue to enlarge during childhood.<ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nThe frontal sinuses only develop in the fifth or sixth year of childhood, and continue expanding throughout adolescence. Each frontal sinus is made up of two independent spaces that develop from two different sources; one from the expansion of ethmoid sinuses into frontal bone, and the other develops from invagination. They never coalesce so drain independently.<ref name=Larsen />\n\n==Function==\n\n=== Respiration ===\n[[File:Mouth and pharynx.png|thumb|Air enters the upper respiratory tract through the nose. The nasal conchae can be seen in this image.]]\nThe nose is the first organ of the [[Respiratory tract|upper respiratory tract]] in the [[respiratory system]]. Its main respiratory function is the supply and conditioning, by warming, moisturising and filtering of [[particulate]]s of inhaled air.<ref name=\"Saladin\"/> [[Nasal hair]] in the nostrils traps large particles preventing their entry into the lungs.<ref name=\"anatomy\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=K |title=Human anatomy |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780071222075 |pages=633\u2013636 |edition=3rd|year=2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe three positioned [[nasal conchae]] in each cavity provide four grooves as air passages, along which the air is circulated and moved to the [[nasopharynx]].<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\">{{cite journal |last1=Van Cauwenberge |first1=P |last2=Sys |first2=L |last3=De Belder |first3=T |last4=Watelet |first4=JB |title=Anatomy and physiology of the nose and the paranasal sinuses. |journal=Immunology and Allergy Clinics of North America |date=February 2004 |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317 |doi=10.1016/S0889-8561(03)00107-3 |pmid=15062424}}</ref> The internal structures and cavities, including the conchae and paranasal sinuses form an integrated system for the conditioning of the air breathed in through the nose.<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\" /> This functioning also includes the major role of the [[nasal mucosa]], and the resulting conditioning of the air before it reaches the lungs is important in maintaining the internal environment and proper functioning of the lungs.<ref name=\"Sahin-Yilmaz\">{{cite journal |last1=Sahin-Yilmaz |first1=A |last2=Naclerio |first2=RM |title=Anatomy and physiology of the upper airway. |journal=Proceedings of the American Thoracic Society |date=March 2011 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=31\u20139 |doi=10.1513/pats.201007-050RN |pmid=21364219}}</ref> The turbulence created by the conchae and meatuses optimises the warming, moistening, and filtering of the mucosa.<ref name=\"Bettejewski\">{{cite journal |last1=Betlejewski |first1=S |last2=Betlejewski |first2=A |title=[The influence of nasal flow aerodynamics on the nasal physiology]. |journal=Otolaryngologia Polska = the Polish Otolaryngology |date=2008 |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=321\u20135 |doi=10.1016/S0030-6657(08)70263-4 |pmid=18652158}}</ref> A major protective role is thereby provided by these structures of the upper respiratory tract, in the passage of air to the more delicate structures of the lower respiratory tract.<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\" />\n\n[[Sneeze|Sneezing]] is an important protective [[reflex action]] initiated by irritation of the [[mucous membrane of nose|nasal mucosa]] to expel unwanted particles through the mouth and nose.<ref name=\"Songu\">{{cite journal |last1=Songu |first1=M |last2=Cingi |first2=C |title=Sneeze reflex: facts and fiction. |journal=Therapeutic Advances in Respiratory Disease |date=June 2009 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=131\u201341 |doi=10.1177/1753465809340571 |pmid=19617285}}</ref> [[Photic sneeze reflex|Photic sneezing]] is a reflex brought on by different stimuli such as bright lights.<ref name=\"Garcia-Moreno\">{{cite journal |date=January 2006 |pmid=16525923|last1=Garc\u00eda-Moreno|first1=J. M.|title=Photic sneeze reflex or autosomal dominant compelling helio-ophthalmic outburst syndrome|journal=Neurologia (Barcelona, Spain)|volume=21|issue=1|pages=26\u201333}}</ref> The nose is also able to provide sense information as to the temperature of the air being breathed.<ref name=\"Geurkink\">{{cite journal |last1=Geurkink |first1=N |title=Nasal anatomy, physiology, and function. |journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology |date=August 1983 |volume=72 |issue=2 |pages=123\u20138 |pmid=6350406|doi=10.1016/0091-6749(83)90518-3 }}</ref>\n\n===Sense of smell===\n[[File:1403 Olfaction.jpg|thumb|The cells lining the nose involved in smell ([[olfaction]]) are shown here]]\nThe nose also plays the major part in the [[olfactory system]]. It contains an area of specialised cells, [[olfactory receptor neuron]]s responsible for the [[olfaction|sense of smell]] (olfaction). [[Olfactory mucosa]] in the upper nasal cavity, contains a type of [[nasal glands|nasal gland]] called [[olfactory gland]]s or Bowman's glands which help in olfaction. The nasal conchae also help in olfaction function, by directing air-flow to the olfactory region.<ref name=\"Bettejewski\"/><ref name=Bluestone>{{cite book|last=Bluestone|first=Charles|title=Pediatric otolaryngology|year=2002|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-7216-9197-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y5rpEdeKtJEC&pg=PA879&dq=nasal+glands#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Speech===\n{{Main|Speech}}\nNormal [[speech]] is produced with pressure from the lungs. This can be modified using airflow through the nose in a process called [[nasalisation]]. This involves the lowering of the soft palate to produce [[nasal vowel]]s and [[Nasal consonant|consonants]] by allowing air to escape from both the nose and the mouth.<ref name=\"Ohala\">{{cite web |last1=Ohala |first1=John |title=The Phonetics of Nasal Phonology:Theorems and Data |url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~ohala/papers/nasal93.pdf |website=berkeley.edu |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> Nasal airflow is also used to produce a variety of [[nasal click]]s called [[click consonant]]s.<ref name=\"Laver\">{{cite book |last1=Laver |first1=John |last2=John |first2=Laver |title=Principles of Phonetics |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zxKCbu536Z8C&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=nasal+clicks#v=onepage&q=nasal%20clicks&f=false |publisher=Cambridge University Press |accessdate=27 November 2019 |language=en |date=12 May 1994|isbn=9780521456555 }}</ref> The large, hollow cavities of the paranasal sinuses act as [[resonance|resonating]] chambers that modify, and amplify speech and other vocal vibrations passing through them.<ref name=\"Saladin2012\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=Kenneth |title=Anatomy & physiology : the unity of form and function |date=2012 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780073378251 |pages=856 |edition=6th}}</ref><ref name=\"T and D\">{{cite book |last1=Tortora |first1=G |title=Principles of anatomy & physiology. |date=2011 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=9780470646083 |page=875 |edition=13th.}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\nOne of the most common medical conditions involving the nose is a [[nosebleed]] (epistaxis). Most nosebleeds occur in [[Kiesselbach's plexus]], a vascular plexus in the lower front part of the septum involving the [[anastamosis|convergence]] of four [[artery|arteries]]. A smaller proportion of nosebleeds that tend to be nontraumatic, occur in [[Woodruff's plexus]]. Woodruff's plexus is a [[venous plexus]] of large thin-walled [[vein]]s lying in the posterior part of the inferior meatus.<ref name=\"Chiu\" />\n\nAnother common condition is [[nasal congestion]], usually a symptom of infection, particularly [[sinusitis]], or other inflammation of the nasal lining called [[rhinitis]], including [[allergic rhinitis]] and [[nonallergic rhinitis]]. Chronic nasal obstruction resulting in breathing through the mouth can greatly impair or prevent the nostrils from flaring.<ref name=\"COA\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Keith |last2=Dalley |first2=Arthur |last3=Agur |first3=Anne |title=Clinically oriented anatomy |date=2018 |publisher=Wolters Kluwer |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=864\u2013869 |edition=Eighth}}</ref> One of the causes of [[snoring]] is nasal obstruction,<ref name=\"mayoclinic\">\"{{cite web |url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/snoring/basics/causes/con-20031874 |title=Snoring Causes |publisher=Mayo Clinic |date=26 April 2015 |website=Mayo Clinic |access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref> and anti-snoring devices such as a [[nasal strip]] help to flare the nostrils and keep the airway open.<ref name=\"COA\"/> '''Nasal flaring''' usually seen in children, happens when breathing is difficult.<ref name=\"flaring\">{{cite web |title=Nasal flaring: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia |url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003055.htm |website=medlineplus.gov |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Most conditions of nasal congestion also cause a loss of the sense of smell ([[anosmia]]). This may also occur in other conditions, for example following trauma, in [[Kallmann syndrome]] or [[Parkinson's disease]]. A blocked sinus ostium, an opening from a paranasal sinus, will cause fluid to accumulate in the sinus.\n\nIn children the nose is a common site of [[foreign bodies]].<ref name=\"urlForeign Body, Nose\">{{cite web |url=http://www.emedicinehealth.com/foreign_body_nose/article_em.htm |title=Foreign Body, Nose |accessdate=2008-12-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220030033/http://www.emedicinehealth.com/foreign_body_nose/article_em.htm |archivedate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> The nose is one of the exposed areas that is susceptible to [[frostbite]].<ref name=\"mayo\">{{cite web |title=Frostbite - Symptoms and causes |url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/frostbite/symptoms-causes/syc-20372656 |website=Mayo Clinic |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the special nature of the blood supply to the human nose and surrounding area, it is possible for retrograde infections from the nasal area to spread to the brain. For this reason, the area from the corners of the mouth to the bridge of the nose, including the nose and [[maxilla]], is known as the [[danger triangle of the face]].<ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nInfections or other conditions that may result in destruction of, or damage to a part of the nose include [[rhinophyma]],<ref name=\"T\u00fcz\u00fcn\">{{cite journal |last1=T\u00fcz\u00fcn |first1=Y |last2=Wolf |first2=R |last3=Kutlubay |first3=Z |last4=Karaku\u015f |first4=O |last5=Engin |first5=B |title=Rosacea and rhinophyma. |journal=Clinics in Dermatology |date=October 2014 |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201346 |doi=10.1016/j.clindermatol.2013.05.024 |pmid=24314376}}</ref> [[skin cancer]]s particularly [[basal-cell carcinoma]],<ref name=\"BSF\">{{cite web |title=Basal Cell Carcinoma |url=https://www.britishskinfoundation.org.uk/bcc |website=British Skin Foundation |language=en}}</ref> [[paranasal sinus and nasal cavity cancer]],<ref name=\"NCI\">{{cite web |title=Paranasal Sinus and Nasal Cavity Cancer Treatment (Adult) (PDQ\u00ae)\u2013Patient Version |url=https://www.cancer.gov/types/head-and-neck/patient/adult/paranasal-sinus-treatment-pdq#_1 |website=National Cancer Institute |language=en |date=8 November 2019}}</ref> [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]],<ref name=\"Coordes\"/> [[syphilis]],<ref name=\"Woods\">{{cite journal |last1=Woods |first1=CR |title=Congenital syphilis-persisting pestilence. |journal=The Pediatric Infectious Disease Journal |date=June 2009 |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=536\u20137 |doi=10.1097/INF.0b013e3181ac8a69 |pmid=19483520 }}</ref> [[leprosy]],{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} [[recreational drug use|recreational use of cocaine]],<ref name=\"Trimarchi\">{{cite journal |last1=Trimarchi |first1=M |last2=Bussi |first2=M |last3=Sinico |first3=RA |last4=Meroni |first4=P |last5=Specks |first5=U |title=Cocaine-induced midline destructive lesions - an autoimmune disease? |journal=Autoimmunity Reviews |date=February 2013 |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=496\u2013500 |doi=10.1016/j.autrev.2012.08.009 |pmid=22940554}}</ref> [[chromium]] and other toxins.<ref name=\"Feron\">{{cite journal |last1=Feron |first1=VJ |last2=Arts |first2=JH |last3=Kuper |first3=CF |last4=Slootweg |first4=PJ |last5=Woutersen |first5=RA |title=Health risks associated with inhaled nasal toxicants. |journal=Critical Reviews in Toxicology |date=May 2001 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=313\u201347 |doi=10.1080/20014091111712 |pmid=11405443}}</ref> The nose may be stimulated to grow in [[acromegaly]], a condition caused by an excess of [[growth hormone]].<ref name=\"NIDDK\">{{cite web |title=Acromegaly {{!}} NIDDK |url=https://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/endocrine-diseases/acromegaly?dkrd=hispt0293 |website=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases}}</ref>\n\nA common anatomic variant is an air-filled cavity within a concha known as a [[concha bullosa]].<ref name=\"Cukurova\">{{cite journal |last1=Cukurova |first1=I |last2=Yaz |first2=A |last3=Gumussoy |first3=M |last4=Yigitbasi |first4=OG |last5=Karaman |first5=Y |title=A patient presenting with concha bullosa in another concha bullosa: a case report. |journal=Journal of Medical Case Reports |date=26 March 2012 |volume=6 |pages=87 |doi=10.1186/1752-1947-6-87 |pmid=22448660|pmc=3338398 }}</ref> In rare cases a polyp can form inside a bullosa.<ref name=\"Erkan\">{{cite journal |last1=Erkan |first1=AN |last2=Canbolat |first2=T |last3=Ozer |first3=C |last4=Yilmaz |first4=I |last5=Ozluoglu |first5=LN |title=Polyp in concha bullosa: a case report and review of the literature. |journal=Head & Face Medicine |date=8 May 2006 |volume=2 |pages=11 |doi=10.1186/1746-160X-2-11 |pmid=16681852|pmc=1471777 }}</ref> Usually a concha bullosa is small and without symptoms but when large can cause obstruction to sinus drainage.<ref name=\"Tapia\">{{cite journal |last1=Rodrigo Tapia |first1=JP |last2=Alvarez Alvarez |first2=I |last3=Casas Rubio |first3=C |last4=Blanco Mercad\u00e9 |first4=A |last5=D\u00edaz Villarig |first5=JL |title=[A giant bilateral concha bullosa causing nasal obstruction]. |journal=Acta Otorrinolaringologica Espanola |date=August 1999 |volume=50 |issue=6 |pages=490\u20132 |pmid=10502705}}</ref>\n\nSome drugs can be [[nasal administration|nasally administered]], and these include [[nasal spray]]s and [[topical medication|topical treatments]].<ref name=\"Geurkink\" /><ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=N |title=The nose and paranasal sinuses physiology and anatomy. |journal=Advanced Drug Delivery Reviews |date=23 September 2001 |volume=51 |issue=1\u20133 |pages=5\u201319 |pmid=11516776|doi=10.1016/S0169-409X(01)00172-7 }}</ref> The septal cartilage can be destroyed through the repeated inhalation of [[recreational drug]]s such as [[cocaine]].  This, in turn, can lead to more widespread collapse of the nasal skeleton.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Menick|first=F|date=November 2014|title=Primary intranasal lining injury cause, deformities, and treatment plan.|url=|journal=Plast Reconstr Surg|volume=134|issue=5|pages=1045\u201356|pmid=25347637|doi=10.1097/PRS.0000000000000694}}</ref>\n\n[[Sneeze|Sneezing]] can transmit infections carried in the expelled droplets. This route is called either [[Transmission (medicine)|airborne transmission]] or [[aerosol]] transmission.<ref name=\"Tellier\">{{cite journal |last1=Tellier |first1=R |last2=Li |first2=Y |last3=Cowling |first3=BJ |last4=Tang |first4=JW |title=Recognition of aerosol transmission of infectious agents: a commentary. |journal=BMC Infectious Diseases |date=31 January 2019 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=101 |doi=10.1186/s12879-019-3707-y |pmid=30704406|pmc=6357359 }}</ref>\n\n===Surgical procedures===\n{{Further|Rhinoplasty}}\n[[File: Ivory artificial nose, Europe, 1701-1800 Wellcome L0058564.jpg|thumb|upright=0.4|[[Prosthesis|Prosthetic nose]] from 17th century Europe.]]\nBadly positioned alar cartilages lack proper support, and can affect the function of the external nasal valve. This can cause breathing problems particularly during deep inhalation.<ref name=\"Silva\">{{cite journal |last1=Silva |first1=EN |title=The Relation Between the Lower Lateral Cartilages and the Function of the External Nasal Valve. |journal=Aesthetic Plastic Surgery |date=February 2019 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=175\u2013183 |doi=10.1007/s00266-018-1195-x |pmid=30019240}}</ref> The surgical procedure to correct breathing problems due to disorders in the nasal structures is called a [[rhinoplasty]], and this is also the procedure used for a [[plastic surgery|cosmetic surgery]] when it is commonly called a \"nose job\". For surgical procedures of rhinoplasty, the nose is mapped out into a number of [[Rhinoplasty|subunits and segments]]. This uses nine ''aesthetic nasal subunits'' and six ''aesthetic nasal segments''. A [[septoplasty]] is the specific surgery to correct a [[nasal septum deviation]].\n\nA [[nasal fracture|broken nose]] can result from trauma. Minor fractures may heal on their own. Surgery known as [[Reduction (orthopedic surgery)|reduction]] may be carried out on more severe breaks that cause dislocation.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=26770280|pmc=4702055|year=2015|last1=K\u00fchnel|first1=T. S.|title=Trauma of the midface|journal=GMS Current Topics in Otorhinolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery|volume=14|pages=Doc06|last2=Reichert|first2=T. E.|doi=10.3205/cto000121}}</ref>\n\nSeveral nasal procedures of the nose and paranasal sinuses can be carried out using [[minimally-invasive procedure|minimally-invasive]] nasal [[endoscope|endoscopy]]. These procedures aim to restore sinus ventilation, mucociliary clearance, and maintain the health of the sinus mucosa.<ref name=\"Kumar\">{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=A |last2=Yadav |first2=N |last3=Singh |first3=N |last4=Chauhan |first4=N |title=Minimally invasive (endoscopic-computer assisted) surgery:Technique and review |journal=Annals of Maxillofacial Surgery |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=159\u2013164 |date=December 2016 |pmid=28299251 |pmc=5343621 |doi=10.4103/2231-0746.200348 }}</ref>\nSome non-nasal surgeries can also be carried out through the use of an endoscope that is entered through the nose. These [[Endoscopic endonasal surgery|endoscopic endonasal surgeries]] are used to remove tumours from the front of the base of the skull.<ref name=\"Komotar\">{{cite journal |last1=Komotar |first1=RJ |last2=Starke |first2=RM |last3=Raper |first3=DM |last4=Anand |first4=VK |last5=Schwartz |first5=TH |title=Endoscopic endonasal compared with microscopic transsphenoidal and open transcranial resection of craniopharyngiomas. |journal=World Neurosurgery |date=February 2012 |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=329\u201341 |doi=10.1016/j.wneu.2011.07.011 |pmid=22501020}}</ref>\n\nSwollen conchae can cause obstruction and [[nasal congestion]], and may be treated surgically by a [[turbinectomy]].<ref name=\"Ye\">{{cite journal |last1=Ye |first1=T |last2=Zhou |first2=B |title=Update on surgical management of adult inferior turbinate hypertrophy. |journal=Current Opinion in Otolaryngology & Head and Neck Surgery |date=February 2015 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=29\u201333 |doi=10.1097/MOO.0000000000000130 |pmid=25565284}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nSome people choose to have [[plastic surgery|cosmetic surgery]] called a [[rhinoplasty]], to change the appearance of their nose. [[Nose piercing]]s are also common, such as in the nostril, septum, or bridge. In certain [[Asia]]n countries such as China, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Thailand and Bangladesh, rhinoplasties are commonly carried out to create a more developed nose bridge or a \"high nose\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/article/1053286/miss-universe-malaysia-pageant-contestants-look-too-western |title=Miss Universe Malaysia pageant contestants 'look too western' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922182526/http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/article/1053286/miss-universe-malaysia-pageant-contestants-look-too-western|archivedate=2016-09-22|date=2018-11-28 }}</ref> Similarly, \"[[Do it yourself|DIY]] nose lifts\" in the form of re-usable cosmetic items have become popular and are sold in many Asian countries such as China, Japan, South Korea, Taiwan, Sri Lanka and Thailand.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/06/diy-plastic-surgery-can-you-change-your-face-without-going-under-the-knife |title=DIY Plastic Surgery: Can You Change Your Face Without Going Under the Knife?|first=Nina |last=Strochlic |date=6 January 2014 |publisher= |newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/thailand/bangkok-post/20161227/282467118553578 |title=Connecting People Through News |website=PressReader |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135827/https://www.pressreader.com/thailand/bangkok-post/20161227/282467118553578 |archivedate=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shybuy.lk/product_info.php/products_id/143|title=Nose Shaper|website=Shybuy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605113816/http://shybuy.lk/product_info.php/products_id/143|archivedate=2017-06-05|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref> A high-bridged nose has been a common beauty ideal in many Asian cultures dating back to the beauty ideals of ancient China and India.<ref>{{cite book|author=Marc S. Abramson|title=Ethnic Identity in Tang China |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-GLGnRspmcAC&pg=PA88|year=2011|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-0101-7 |page=88 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502191609/https://books.google.com/books?id=-GLGnRspmcAC&pg=PA88|archivedate=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Johann Jakob Meyer|title=Sexual Life in Ancient India: A Study in the Comparative History of Indian Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izFNswlJ9LMC&pg=PA433|year=1989|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0638-2 |page=433 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502191609/https://books.google.com/books?id=izFNswlJ9LMC&pg=PA433|archivedate=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn [[New Zealand]], nose pressing (\"[[hongi]]\") is a traditional [[greeting]] originating among the [[M\u0101ori people]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Derby|first1=Mark|title=Ng\u0101 mahi tika|url=https://www.teara.govt.nz/en/nga-mahi-tika|publisher=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=8 September 2017|date=September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908020350/https://www.teara.govt.nz/en/nga-mahi-tika|archivedate=8 September 2017}}</ref> However it is now generally confined to certain traditional celebrations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.polynesia.com/blog/greetings-hongi-style/|title=Greetings! Hongi Style! \u2013 polynesia.com {{!}} blog|date=2016-03-24|work=polynesia.com {{!}} blog|access-date=2017-09-18|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918155352/http://www.polynesia.com/blog/greetings-hongi-style/|archivedate=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hanazuka]] monument enshrines the mutilated noses of at least 38,000 Koreans killed during the Japanese invasions of Korea from 1592 to 1598.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sansom |first=George Bailey |title=A History of Japan, 1334\u20131615 |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofjapan00sans |url-access=registration |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1961 |series=Stanford studies in the civilizations of eastern Asia|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofjapan00sans/page/360 360]|isbn=978-0-8047-0525-7 |quote=Visitors to Kyoto used to be shown the Minizuka or Ear Tomb, which contained, it was said, the noses of those 38,000, sliced off, suitably pickled, and sent to Kyoto as evidence of victory. }}</ref>\n\n[[Nose-picking]] is a common, mildly [[taboo]] habit. Medical risks include the spread of infections, nosebleeds and, rarely, [[nasal septum perforation|perforation of the nasal septum]]. When it becomes compulsive it is termed [[rhinotillexomania]]. The wiping of the nose with the hand, commonly referred to as the \"[[allergic salute]]\", is also mildly taboo and can result in the spreading of infections as well. Habitual as well as fast or rough nose wiping may also result in a crease (known as a [[transverse nasal crease]] or groove) running across the nose, and can lead to permanent physical deformity observable in childhood and adulthood.<ref name=pray221>{{cite book|last=Pray|first=W. Steven |title=Nonprescription Product Therapeutics|year=2005|publisher=[[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]]|location=p. 221|isbn=978-0781734981}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Mitali Ruths |url=http://www.livestrong.com/article/296252-white-line-on-nose-in-children/ |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=2012-11-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622025144/http://www.livestrong.com/article/296252-white-line-on-nose-in-children/ |archivedate=2012-06-22 |title=White Line on Nose in Children |website=LiveStrong.com }}</ref>\n\n[[Nose fetishism]] (or nasophilia) is the sexual [[partialism]] for the nose.<ref name=\"freedict\">{{cite web |title=nasophilia |url=https://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/nasophilia |website=The Free Dictionary}}</ref>\n\n==Neanderthals==\n[[Clive Finlayson]] of the [[Gibraltar Museum]] said the large [[Neanderthal]] noses were an adaption to the cold,<ref>{{cite book | last = Finlayson | first = C | title = Neanderthals and modern humans: an ecological and evolutionary perspective | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-521-82087-5 | pages = [https://books.google.com/books?id=TmQ4i1EQ4AYC&pg=PA84 84] }}</ref> Todd C. Rae of the [[American Museum of Natural History]] said primate and arctic animal studies have shown sinus size reduction in areas of extreme cold rather than enlargement in accordance with [[Allen's rule]].<ref name=\"Rae\" /> Therefore, Todd C. Rae concludes that the design of the large and [[Wiktionary:prognathous#English|prognathic]] Neanderthal nose was evolved for the hotter climate of the Middle East and Africa and remained unchanged when they entered Europe <ref name=\"Rae\">{{cite journal | last1 = Rae | first1 = T.C. | year = 2011 | title = The Neanderthal face is not cold adapted | url = | journal = Journal of Human Evolution | volume = 60 | issue = 2| pages = 234\u2013239 | doi=10.1016/j.jhevol.2010.10.003 | pmid=21183202}}</ref>\n\nMiquel Hern\u00e1ndez of the Department of Animal Biology at the [[University of Barcelona]] said the \"high and narrow nose of [[Eskimos]] and [[Neanderthals]]\" is an \"adaption to a cold and dry environment\", since it contributes to warming and moisturizing the air and the \"recovery of heat and moisture from expired air\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hern\u00e1ndez | first1 = M. | last2 = Fox | first2 = C. L. | last3 = Garcia-Moro | first3 = C. | year = 1997 | title = Fueguian cranial morphology: The adaptation to a cold, harsh environment | url = | journal = American Journal of Physical Anthropology | volume = 103 | issue = 1| pages = 103\u2013117 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1096-8644(199705)103:1<103::AID-AJPA7>3.0.CO;2-X | pmid=9185954}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Empty nose syndrome]], a nose crippled by excessive resection of the inferior and/or middle [[turbinates]] of the nose\n* [[Nasothek]]\n* [[Neti (Hatha Yoga)]], an [[Ayurvedic]] technique of [[nasal irrigation|nasal cleansing]]\n* [[Sr\u00f2n]], the [[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]] word for nose and the name of some hills in the [[Scottish Highlands]]\n\n==References==\n{{Gray's}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Human noses}}\n* {{Wikiquote inline|Noses}}\n\n{{Nose anatomy}}\n{{Human regional anatomy}}\n{{Human systems and organs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Facial features]]\n[[Category:Nose]]\n[[Category:Human anatomy|nose]]\n[[Category:Human head and neck]]\n[[Category:Sensory organs]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Nose (disambiguation)}}\n{{about|noses in humans|the article about noses in general|nose}}\n\n{{Infobox anatomy\n| Name        = Human nose\n| Latin       = nasus\n| Greek       = \n| Image       = Fort Ross Elena wearing Traditional Russian Costume (cropped).jpg\n| Caption     = View of human nose\n| Width       = 240\n| Image2      = Head Olfactory Nerve Labeled.png\n| Caption2    = Cross-section of the interior of a nose showing parts involved in smell ([[olfactory system|olfaction]])\n| Precursor   = \n| System      = \n| Artery      = [[sphenopalatine artery]], [[greater palatine artery]]\n| Vein        = [[facial vein]]\n| Nerve       = [[external nasal nerve]]\n| Lymph       = \n}}\nThe '''human nose''' is the most protruding part of the [[face]].  It bears the [[nostril]]s and is the first organ of the [[respiratory system]].  It is also the principal organ in the [[olfactory system]].  The shape of the [[nose]] is determined by the [[nasal bone]]s and the [[nasal cartilages]], including the [[nasal septum]] which separates the nostrils and divides the [[nasal cavity]] into two. On average the nose of a [[male]] is larger than that of a [[female]].\n\nThe main function of the nose is [[breathing]], and the [[nasal mucosa]] lining the nasal cavity and the [[paranasal sinuses]] carries out the necessary conditioning of inhaled air by warming and moistening it. [[Nasal concha]]e, [[Conch|shell-like]] bones in the walls of the cavities, play a major part in this process. Filtering of the air by [[nasal hair]] in the nostrils prevents large particles from entering the lungs. [[Sneezing]] is a [[reflex]] to expel unwanted particles from the nose that irritate the mucosal lining. Sneezing can [[Transmission (medicine)|transmit infections]], because [[aerosol]]s are created in which the [[Respiratory droplets|droplets]] can harbour [[pathogen]]s.\n\nAnother major function of the nose is [[olfaction]], the sense of smell. The area of [[olfactory epithelium]], in the upper nasal cavity, contains specialised [[olfactory cells]] responsible for this function.\n\nThe nose is also involved in the function of speech. [[Nasal vowel]]s and [[nasal consonant]]s are produced in the process of [[nasalisation]]. The hollow cavities of the paranasal sinuses act as sound chambers that modify and amplify speech and other vocal sounds.\n\nThere are many [[plastic surgery]] procedures on the nose, known as [[Rhinoplasty|rhinoplasties]] available to correct various structural defects or to change the shape of the nose. Defects may be [[Birth defect|congenital]], or result from nasal disorders or from trauma. These procedures are a type of [[plastic surgery#Reconstructive surgery|reconstructive surgery]]. [[Elective surgery|Elective procedures]] to change a nose shape are a type of [[plastic surgery#Cosmetic surgery procedures|cosmetic surgery]].\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Structure==\nSeveral [[bone]]s and [[cartilage]]s make up the bony-cartilaginous framework of the nose, and the internal structure.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The nose is also made up of types of [[soft tissue]] such as [[skin]], [[epithelium|epithelia]], [[mucous membrane]], [[muscle]]s, [[nerve]]s, and [[blood vessel]]s. In the skin there are [[sebaceous gland]]s, and in the mucous membrane there are [[nasal glands]].<ref name=\"Singh\" /> The bones and cartilages provide strong protection for the internal structures of the nose. There are several muscles that are involved in movements of the nose. The arrangement of the cartilages allows flexibility through muscle control to enable airflow to be modified.<ref name=\"Singh\" />\n\n===Bones===\n[[File:714 Bone of Nasal Cavity.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Bones of the nose and septal cartilage]]\n[[File: Sobo 1909 100.png|thumb|Roof of the mouth showing position of palatine bones making up the floor of the nose, and forming the [[posterior nasal spine]] for the attachment of the [[musculus uvulae]].]]\nThe bony structure of the nose is provided by the [[maxilla]], [[frontal bone]], and a number of smaller bones.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\">{{cite book |last1=Standring |first1=Susan |title=Gray's anatomy : the anatomical basis of clinical practice |date=2016 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9780702052309 |pages=556\u2013565 |edition=Forty-first}}</ref>\n\n<!-- From top to bottom -->The topmost bony part of the nose is formed by the nasal part of the frontal bone, which lies between the brow ridges,<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> and ends in a serrated [[nasal notch]].<ref name=\"Gray's E-Book\">{{cite book |last1=Standring |first1=Susan |title=Gray's Anatomy E-Book: The Anatomical Basis of Clinical Practice |url=https://books.google.com/?id=b7FVCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA479&lpg=PA479&dq=nasal+notch#v=onepage&q=nasal%20notch&f=false |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |language=en |date=7 August 2015|isbn=9780702068515 }}</ref> A left and a right [[nasal bone]] join with the nasal part of the frontal bone at either side; and these at the side with the small [[lacrimal bone]]s and the [[Frontal process of maxilla|frontal process of each maxilla]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The internal roof of the nasal cavity is composed of the horizontal, perforated [[cribriform plate]] of the [[ethmoid bone]] through which pass [[Axon#Sensory|sensory fibres]] of the [[olfactory nerve]]. Below and behind the cribriform plate, sloping down at an angle, is the face of the [[sphenoid bone]].\n\nThe wall separating the two cavities of the nose, the [[nasal septum]], is made up of bone inside and cartilage closer to the tip of the nose.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The bony part is formed by the [[Perpendicular plate of ethmoid bone|perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone]] at the top, and the [[vomer|vomer bone]] below.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The floor of the nose is made up of the [[incisive bone]] and the [[Horizontal plate of palatine bone|horizontal plates of the palatine bones]], and this makes up the [[hard palate]] of the roof of the mouth. The two horizontal plates join together at the midline and form the [[posterior nasal spine]] that gives attachment to the [[musculus uvulae]] in the [[uvula]].\n\nThe two maxilla bones join at the base of the nose at the lower nasal midline between the nostrils, and at the top of the [[philtrum]] to form the [[anterior nasal spine]]. This thin projection of bone holds the cartilaginous center of the nose.<ref name=\"Knipe\">{{cite web |last1=Knipe |first1=Henry |title=Anterior nasal spine fracture {{!}} Radiology Case {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/cases/anterior-nasal-spine-fracture |website=radiopaedia.org |accessdate=24 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeologyinfo.com/archaeology-evolution-glossary-n/|title=Glossary: nasal spine (anterior)|publisher=ArchaeologyInfo.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301183829/http://archaeologyinfo.com/archaeology-evolution-glossary-n/|archive-date=2017-03-01|url-status=live|accessdate=2017-02-28}}</ref> It is also an important [[Cephalometric analysis#Cephalometric landmarks|cephalometric landmark]].<ref>Dory, Miri (March 13, 2014). [http://www.cephx.com/cephalometric-analysis/ \"Cephalometric analysis\"], Cephx.</ref>\n\n===Cartilages===\n[[File:Gray852.png|thumb|upright=0.6|left|Nasal cartilages]]\nThe [[nasal cartilages]] are the [[septal nasal cartilage|septal]], [[lateral nasal cartilage|lateral]], [[major alar cartilage|major alar]], and [[minor alar cartilage|minor alar]] cartilages.<ref name=\"Lang\">{{cite book |last1=Lang |first1=Johannes |title=Clinical Anatomy of the Nose, Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses |url=https://books.google.com/?id=afNfhoxkDeoC&pg=PA10&dq=nasal+cartilages#v=onepage&q=nasal%20cartilages&f=false |publisher=Thieme |language=en |date=1989|isbn=9783137384014 }}</ref> The major and minor cartilages are also known as the greater and lesser alar cartilages. There is a narrow strip of cartilage called the [[vomeronasal cartilage]] that lies between the [[vomer]] and the septal cartilage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vomeronasal cartilage |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/medical/vomeronasal%20cartilage}}</ref>\n\nThe [[septal nasal cartilage]], extends from the nasal bones in the midline, to the bony part of the [[nasal septum|septum]] in the midline, posteriorly. It then passes along the floor of the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Schunke\">{{cite book |last1=Sch\u00fcnke |first1=Michael |last2=Ross |first2=Lawrence M. |last3=Schulte |first3=Erik |last4=Lamperti |first4=Edward D. |last5=Schumacher |first5=Udo |title=Thieme Atlas of Anatomy: Head and Neuroanatomy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wlGDPwz_7KoC&pg=PA18&dq=Lateral+nasal+cartilage#v=onepage&q=Lateral%20nasal%20cartilage&f=false |publisher=Thieme |language=en |date=2007|isbn=9781588904416 }}</ref> The septum is quadrangular\u2013the upper half is attached to the two [[lateral nasal cartilages]] which are fused to the dorsal septum in the midline. The septum is laterally attached, with loose ligaments, to the bony margin of the [[anterior nasal aperture]], while the inferior ends of the lateral cartilages are free (unattached). The three or four [[minor alar cartilage]]s are adjacent to the lateral cartilages, held in the [[connective tissue]] membrane, that connects the lateral cartilages to the frontal process of the maxilla.\n\nThe nasal bones in the upper part of the nose are joined together by the midline [[nasal bone|internasal suture]]. They join with the [[Septal nasal cartilage|septal cartilage]] at a junction known as the '''rhinion'''. The rhinion is the midpoint of the internasal suture at the join with the cartilage, and from the rhinion to the apex, or tip, the framework is of cartilage.\n\nThe [[major alar cartilage]]s are thin, U-shaped plates of cartilage on each side of the nose that form the lateral and medial walls of the vestibule, known as the medial and lateral crura. The medial crura are attached to the septal cartilage, forming fleshy parts at the front of the nostrils on each side of the septum, called the ''medial crural footpods''. The medial crura meet at the midline below the end of the septum to form the '''columella'''<ref name=\"Bell\">{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Daniel J. |title=Columella {{!}} Radiology Reference Article {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/articles/columella |website=Radiopaedia}}</ref> and '''lobule'''. The lobule contains the tip of the nose and its base contains the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> At the peaks of the folds of the medial crura, they form the '''alar domes''' the tip-defining points of the nose, separated by a notch.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> They then fold outwards, above and to the side of the nostrils forming the lateral crura.<ref name=\"Ballenger\" /><ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book |last1=Singh |first1=Vishram |title=Textbook of anatomy head, neck and brain. Volume 3 |date=2014 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9788131237274 |pages=251\u2013263 |edition=Second}}</ref> The major alar cartilages are freely moveable and can respond to muscles to either open or constrict the nostrils.<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Keith |last2=Dalley |first2=Arthur |last3=Agur |first3=Anne |title=Clinically oriented anatomy |date=2018 |publisher=Wolters Kluwer |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=963\u2013973 |edition=Eighth}}</ref>\n\nThere is a reinforcing structure known as the '''nasal scroll''' that resists internal collapse from airflow pressure generated by normal breathing. This structure is formed by the junction between the lateral and major cartilages. Their edges interlock by one scrolling upwards and one scrolling inwards.<ref name=\"Ballenger\">{{cite book |last1=Ballenger |first1=John Jacob |last2=Snow |first2=James Byron |title=Ballenger's Otorhinolaryngology: Head and Neck Surgery |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BastAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA643&lpg=PA643&dq=nasal+scroll#v=onepage&q=nasal%20scroll&f=false |publisher=PMPH-USA |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en |date=2003|isbn=9781550091977 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gubisch\">{{cite book |last1=Gubisch |first1=Wolfgang |title=Mastering Advanced Rhinoplasty |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KR4-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&dq=nasal+scroll#v=onepage&q=nasal%20scroll&f=false |publisher=Springer |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en |date=10 November 2017|isbn=9783319675374 }}</ref>\n\n===Muscles===\nThe muscles of the nose are a subgroup of the [[muscles of facial expression]]. They are involved in respiration and facial expression. The muscles of the nose include the procerus, nasalis, depressor septi nasalis, levator labii superioris alaeque nasalis, and the orbicularis oris of the mouth. As are all of the facial muscles, the muscles of the nose are innervated by the facial nerve and its branches.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Although each muscle is independent, the muscles of the nose form a continuous layer with connections between all the components of the muscles and ligaments, in the nasal part of a [[superficial muscular aponeurotic system]] (SMAS).<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"  /><ref name=\"Saban\">{{cite journal |last1=Saban |first1=Y |last2=Andretto Amodeo |first2=C |last3=Hammou |first3=JC |last4=Polselli |first4=R |title=An anatomical study of the nasal superficial musculoaponeurotic system: surgical applications in rhinoplasty. |journal=Archives of Facial Plastic Surgery |date=2009 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=109\u201315 |doi=10.1001/archfaci.10.2.109 |pmid=18347238}}</ref> The SMAS is continuous from the nasofrontal process to the nasal tip. It divides at level of the nasal valve  into superficial and deep layers, each layer having medial and lateral components.<ref name=\"Saban\" />\n\nThe [[procerus muscle]] produces wrinkling over the bridge of the nose, and is active in concentration and frowning. It is a prime target for [[Botulinum toxin#Cosmetics|Botox procedures]] in the forehead to remove the lines between the eyes.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[nasalis muscle]] consists of two main parts: a transverse part called the [[compressor naris]], and an alar part termed the [[dilator naris muscle|dilator naris]].  The compressor naris muscle compresses the nostrils and may completely close them. The alar part, the dilator naris mainly consists of the dilator naris posterior, and a much smaller dilator naris anterior, and this muscle flares the nostrils. The dilator naris helps to form the upper ridge of the philtrum.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The anterior, and the posterior dilator naris, (the alar part of the nasalis muscle), give support to the nasal valves.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[Depressor septi nasi muscle|depressor septi muscle]] may sometimes be absent or rudimentary.  The depressor septi pulls the columella, the septum, and the tip of the nose downwards. At the start of inspiration this muscle tenses the nasal septum and with the dilator naris widens the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe [[levator labii superioris alaeque nasi]],  divides into a medial and a lateral slip. The medial slip blends into the perichondrium of the major alar cartilage and its overlying skin. The lateral slip blends at the side of the upper lip with the [[levator labii superioris]], and with the [[orbicularis oris]].  The lateral slip raises the upper lip and deepens  and increases the curve above the nasolabial furrow. The medial slip pulls the lateral crus upwards and modifies the curve of the furrow around the alae, and dilates the nostrils.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Soft tissue===\n\nThe skin of the nose varies in thickness along its length.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> From the glabella to the bridge (the nasofrontal angle) the skin is thick, fairly flexible, and mobile. It tapers to the bridge where it is thinnest and least flexible as it is closest to the underlying bone.  From the bridge until the tip of the nose the skin is thin. The tip is covered in skin that is as thick as the top section, and has many large sebaceous glands.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name= \"Moore\" />\nThe thickness of the skin varies but is still separated from the underlying bones and cartilage by four layers \u2013 a superficial  [[panniculus adiposus|fatty layer]]; a [[connective tissue#Types|fibromuscular layer]] continued from the [[Superficial muscular aponeurotic system|SMAS]]; a deep fatty layer, and the [[periosteum]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nOther areas of [[soft tissue]] are found where there is no support from cartilage - these include an area around the sides of the septum - the paraseptal area; an area around the lateral cartliages; an area at the top of the nostril, and an area in the alae.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===External nose===\n\nThe nasal root is the top of the nose that attaches the nose to the [[forehead]].<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The nasal root is above the [[nasal bridge|bridge]] and below the [[glabella]], forming an indentation known as the [[nasion]] at the frontonasal suture where the [[frontal bone]] meets the nasal bones.<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite web |title=Nasion definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary |url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/nasion |website=www.collinsdictionary.com |accessdate=2019-11-06 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe '''nasal dorsum''' also known as the ''nasal ridge'' is the border between the root and the tip of the nose which in profile can be variously shaped.<ref name=\"TortAnag\">{{cite book |last1=Tortora |first1=G |last2=Anagnostakos |first2=N |title=Principles of anatomy and physiology |url=https://archive.org/details/principlesofan1987tort |url-access=registration |date=1987 |publisher=Harper & Row |isbn=978-0063507296 |page=[https://archive.org/details/principlesofan1987tort/page/556 556] |edition=5th. Harper international}}</ref>\n\nThe '''ala of the nose''' (ala nasi, wing of the nose) is the lower lateral surface of the external nose, shaped by the alar cartilage and covered in dense connective tissue.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The alae flare out to form a rounded eminence around the [[nostril]].<ref name=\"TortAnag\" />\n\n[[Sexual dimorphism]] is evident in the larger nose of the male. This is due to the increased [[testosterone]] that thickens the [[brow ridge]] and the bridge of the nose making it wider.<ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unl.edu/rhames/courses/male_facial_beauty.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130021737/http://www.unl.edu/rhames/courses/male_facial_beauty.htm |archivedate=2007-11-30 }}</ref>\n\n===Nasal cavity===\n{{Main|Nasal cavity}}\n[[File:Anatomy of the human nasal cavity.png|thumb|Anatomy of the nasal cavity. [[Nasal-associated lymphoid tissue]] labelled NALT|alt=]]\nThe [[nasal cavity]] is the large internal space of the nose, and is in two parts \u2013 the [[Nasal cavity#Structure|nasal vestibule]] and the nasal cavity proper.<ref name=\"Singh\" /> The nasal vestibule is the frontmost part of the [[nasal cavity]], enclosed by cartilages.  The vestibule is lined with skin, hair follicles, and a large number of sebaceous glands.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /><ref name=\"Singh\" /> A mucous ridge known as the '''limen nasi''' separates the vestibule from the rest of the nasal cavity and marks the change from the skin of the vestibule to the [[respiratory epithelium]] of the rest of the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Singh\" /> This area is also known as a [[mucocutaneous junction]] and has a dense [[microvasculature]]. <ref name=\"Wolfram-Gabel\">{{cite journal |last1=Wolfram-Gabel |first1=R |last2=Sick |first2=H |title=Microvascularization of the mucocutaneous junction of the nose. |journal=Surgical and Radiologic Anatomy |date=February 2002 |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |pmid=12197007|doi=10.1007/s00276-002-0009-6 }}</ref>\n\nThe nasal cavity is divided into two cavities by the nasal septum, and each is accessed by an external nostril.<ref name=\"Moore\" /><ref name=\"anatomy\" /> The division into two cavities enables the functioning of the [[Nasal cycle#Benefits in breathing|nasal cycle]] that slows down the conditioning process of the inhaled air.<ref name=\"Hummel\">{{citation|author1=Thomas Hummel|author2=Antje Welge-L\u00fcssen|title=Taste and Smell: An Update|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fuxS-p6bpuwC&pg=PA12|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-8055-8123-3|pages=12\u2013}}</ref>\nAt the back of the nasal cavity there are two openings, called [[choana]]e (also ''posterior nostrils''), that give entrance to the [[nasopharynx]], and rest of the [[respiratory tract]].<ref name=\"anatomy\" />\n\nOn the outer wall of each cavity are three shell-like bones called [[nasal concha|conchae]], arranged as [[superior nasal concha|superior]], [[middle nasal concha|middle]] and [[inferior nasal concha]]e. Below each concha is a corresponding superior, middle, and inferior [[nasal meatus]], or passage.<ref name=\"anatomy\" /> Sometimes when the superior concha is narrow, a fourth supreme nasal concha is present situated above and sharing the space with the superior concha.<ref name=\"Navarro\">{{cite book |last1=Navarro |first1=Joao A. C. |title=The Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: Surgical Anatomy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=dJnvCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=supreme+nasal+concha#v=onepage&q=supreme%20nasal%20concha&f=false |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en |date=6 December 2012|isbn=9783642568299 }}</ref> The term concha refers to the actual bone - when covered by soft tissue and mucosa, and functioning, a concha is termed a '''turbinate'''.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nMost of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is lined with [[respiratory epithelium]] as [[nasal mucosa]]. In the roof of each cavity is an area of specialised [[olfactory epithelium]]. This region is about 5 square cm, covering the superior concha, the cribriform plate, and the nasal septum.<ref name=\"McGraw\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=Kenneth |title=Anatomy & physiology : the unity of form and function |date=2012 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=978-0073378251 |pages=593\u2013595 |edition=6th}}</ref>\n\nThere is a '''nasal valve''' area that is the narrowest part of the nasal passage. An external valve exists in the larger ala part of the vestibule. An internal nasal valve typically referred to as the nasal valve, is a slit-like segment between part of the upper lateral cartilage and the septum in the middle third of the cavity.<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite journal |last1=Becker |first1=DG |last2=Becker |first2=SS |title=Treatment of nasal obstruction from nasal valve collapse with alar batten grafts. |journal=Journal of Long-Term Effects of Medical Implants |date=2003 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=259\u201369 |pmid=14516189|doi=10.1615/JLongTermEffMedImplants.v13.i3.100 }}</ref><ref name=\"Pecorari\">{{cite journal |last1=Pecorari |first1=G |last2=Riva |first2=G |last3=Bianchi |first3=FA |last4=Cavallo |first4=G |last5=Revello |first5=F |last6=Bironzo |first6=M |last7=Verz\u00e8 |first7=L |last8=Garzaro |first8=M |last9=Ramieri |first9=G |title=The effect of closed septorhinoplasty on nasal functions and on external and internal nasal valves: A prospective study. |journal=American Journal of Rhinology & Allergy |date=1 September 2017 |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=323\u2013327 |doi=10.2500/ajra.2017.31.4459 |pmid=28859710}}</ref> The valves regulate the airflow and resistance. Air breathed in is forced to pass through the narrow internal nasal valve, and then expands as it moves into the nasal cavity. The sudden change in the speed and pressure of the airflow creates turbulence that allows optimum contact with the respiratory epithelium for the necessary warming, moisturising, and filtering. The turbulence also allows movement of the air to pass over the olfactory epithelium and transfer odor information.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"/> The angle of the valve between the septum and the sidewall needs to be sufficient for unobstructed airflow,<ref name=\"Fischer\">{{cite journal |last1=Fischer |first1=H |last2=Gubisch |first2=W |title=Nasal valves--importance and surgical procedures. |journal=Facial Plastic Surgery |date=November 2006 |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=266\u201380 |doi=10.1055/s-2006-954845 |pmid=17131269|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5347f92dbb17b43df59832f5c5c311f0cf733b48 }}</ref> and this is normally between 10 and 15 degrees.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\"/>\n\nThe borders of each nasal cavity are a roof, floor, medial wall (the septum), and lateral wall.<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The middle part of the roof of the nasal cavity is composed of the horizontal, perforated [[cribriform plate]] of the [[ethmoid bone]], through which pass [[Axon#Sensory|sensory fibres]] of the [[olfactory nerve]] into the cranial cavity.<ref name=\"Singh\" />\n\n====Paranasal sinuses====\n{{Main|Paranasal sinuses}}\n[[File:724 Paranasal Sinuses.jpg|thumb|Paranasal sinuses]]\nThe [[respiratory epithelium|mucosa]] that lines the nasal cavity extends into its chambers, the [[paranasal sinuses]].<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The nasal cavity and the paranasal sinuses are referred to as the ''sinonasal tract'' or ''sinonasal region'', and its anatomy is recognised as being unique and complex.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis JS |first1=Jr |title=Sinonasal Squamous Cell Carcinoma: A Review with Emphasis on Emerging Histologic Subtypes and the Role of Human Papillomavirus. |journal=Head and Neck Pathology |date=March 2016 |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=60\u201367 |doi=10.1007/s12105-016-0692-y |pmid=26830402|pmc=4746138 }}</ref><ref name=\"HandN\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis |first1=J |title=The sinonasal tract: another potential \"hot spot\" for carcinomas with transcriptionally-active human papillomavirus. |journal=Head and Neck Pathology |date=2014 |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=241\u20139 |doi=10.1007/s12105-013-0514-4 |pmid=24338611|pmc=4126925 }}</ref>\n\nFour paired paranasal sinuses drain into regions of the nasal cavity.\nThe sinuses are air-filled extensions of the nasal cavity into the cranial bones.<ref name=\"Moore\" /> The frontal sinuses are located in the frontal bone; the sphenoidal sinuses in the sphenoid bone; the maxillary sinuses in the maxilla; and the ethmoidal sinuses in the ethmoid bone.<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nA narrow opening called a [[sinus ostium]] from each of the paranasal sinuses allows drainage into the nasal cavity. The maxillary sinus is the largest of the sinuses and drains into the middle meatus. Most of the ostia open into the middle meatus and the anterior ethmoid, that together are termed the [[Nasal cavity#Structure|ostiomeatal complex]].<ref name=\"Wagenmann\">{{cite journal |last1=Wagenmann |first1=M |last2=Naclerio |first2=RM |title=Anatomic and physiologic considerations in sinusitis. |journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology |date=September 1992 |volume=90 |issue=3 Pt 2 |pages=419\u201323 |doi=10.1016/0091-6749(92)90161-t |pmid=1527330}}</ref> Adults have a high concentration of cilia in the ostia.The cilia in the sinuses beat towards the openings into the nasal cavity. The increased cilia and the narrowness of the sinus openings allow for an increased time for moisturising, and warming.<ref name=\"Wagenmann\" />\n\nExcessive moisture as tears collected in the [[lacrimal sac]] travel down the [[nasolacrimal duct]]s where they drain into the inferior meatus in the nasal cavity.<ref name=\"Saladin\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=K |title=Human anatomy |date=2011 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780071222075 |page=480 |edition=3rd}}</ref>\n\n===Nose shape===\nThe shape of the nose varies widely due to differences in the nasal bone shapes and formation of the bridge of the nose. Some nose shapes were classified for [[rhinoplasty|surgeries]] by Eden Warwick in ''Nasology'' 1848:\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Class_I_nose.jpg| Class I. The [[aquiline nose]]. \nFile:Class_II_nose.jpg| Class II. The Grecian nose. \nFile:Class_III_nose.jpg| Class III. The African nose. \nFile:Class_IV_nose.jpg| Class IV. The hawk nose. \nFile:Class_V_nose.jpg| Class V. The snub nose. \nFile:Class_VI_nose.jpg| Class VI. The celestial nose. \n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Topinard nasal index.png|thumb|Nose shapes used in [[Paul Topinard|Topinard's]] nasal index]]\n[[Paul Topinard]] developed the [[Herbert Hope Risley#Ethnographic Survey of Bengal:1885-91|nasal index]] as a method of classifying ethnic groups. The index is based on the ratio of the breadth of the nose to its height.<ref name=\"Leong\">{{cite journal |last1=Leong |first1=SC |last2=Eccles |first2=R |title=A systematic review of the nasal index and the significance of the shape and size of the nose in rhinology. |journal=Clinical Otolaryngology |date=June 2009 |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=191\u20138 |doi=10.1111/j.1749-4486.2009.01905.x |pmid=19531167}}</ref> The nasal dimensions are also used to classify nasal morphology into five types: ''Hyperleptorrhine'' is a very long, narrow nose with a nasal index of 40 to 55.<ref name=\"Index\"/> ''Leptorrhine'' describes a long, narrow nose with an index of 55\u201370.<ref name=\"Index\"/> ''Mesorrhine'' is a medium nose with an index of 70\u201385. ''Platyrrhine'' is a short, broad nose with an index of 85\u201399\u00b79. The fifth type is the ''hyperplatyrrhine'' having an index of more than 100.<ref name=\"Index\">{{cite web |title=Anthropometric_evaluation_of_nasal_height_nasal_breadth_and_nasal_index_among_Bini_children_In_Southern_Nigeria |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/332912694 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome deformities of the nose are named, such as the '''pug nose''' and the [[saddle nose]]. The pug nose is characterised by excess tissue from the apex that is out of proportion to the rest of the nose. A low and underdeveloped nasal bridge may also be evident.<ref name=\"Roe\">{{cite journal |last1=Roe |first1=J. O. |title=The Deformity Termed 'Pug Nose' and Its Correction by a Simple Operation |issue=2 |journal=Archives of Otolaryngology\u2013Head & Neck Surgery |volume=115 |pages=156\u2013157 |language=en |doi=10.1001/archotol.1989.01860260030010 |pmid=2643972 |date=1 February 1989}}</ref> A saddle nose is mostly associated with trauma to the nose but can be caused by other conditions including [[leprosy]].<ref name=\"Coordes\">{{cite journal |last1=Coordes |first1=A |last2=Loose |first2=SM |last3=Hofmann |first3=VM |last4=Hamilton GS |first4=3rd |last5=Riedel |first5=F |last6=Menger |first6=DJ |last7=Albers |first7=AE |title=Saddle nose deformity and septal perforation in granulomatosis with polyangiitis. |journal=Clinical Otolaryngology |date=February 2018 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=291\u2013299 |doi=10.1111/coa.12977 |pmid=28881107}}</ref>\n\n[[Werner syndrome]], a condition that causes the appearance of premature aging, causes a \"bird-like\" appearance due to pinching of the nose.<ref name=\"Leis\">{{cite book |vauthors=Oshima J, Martin GM, Hisama FM |veditors=Adam MP, Ardinger HH, Pagon RA|display-editors=etal |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1514/ |title=Werner Syndrome |date=2002-12-02 |orig-year=Updated 2016-09-29 |work=GeneReviews\u00ae |location=Seattle, WA |publisher=University of Washington |via=NCBI |accessdate=2017-08-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118125119/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1514/ |archivedate=2017-01-18 }}</ref>\n\n[[Down syndrome]] commonly presents a small nose with a flattened nasal bridge. This can be due to the absence of one or both  nasal bones, shortened nasal bones, or nasal bones that have not fused in the midline.<ref name=\"Sonek\">{{cite journal |last1=Sonek |first1=JD |last2=Cicero |first2=S |last3=Neiger |first3=R |last4=Nicolaides |first4=KH |title=Nasal bone assessment in prenatal screening for trisomy 21. |journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology |date=November 2006 |volume=195 |issue=5 |pages=1219\u201330 |doi=10.1016/j.ajog.2005.11.042 |pmid=16615922}}</ref><ref name=\"Persico\">{{cite journal |last1=Persico|display-authors=etal|first1=N |title=Nasal bone assessment in fetuses with trisomy 21 at 16-24 weeks of gestation by three-dimensional ultrasound. |journal=Prenatal Diagnosis |date=March 2012 |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=240\u20134 |doi=10.1002/pd.2938 |pmid=22430721|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/24e76ebcd06a61538da3b98dedab4b6c7e744fd7}}</ref>\n\n==Blood supply and drainage==\n===Supply===\n[[File:Blausen 0170 CarotidArteries.png|thumb|Carotid arteries]]\n[[File:Arteries of the Nose.jpg|thumb|Multiple arteries supply blood to the nose; the nasal septum, shown here is supplied by the anterior and posterior ethmoidal arteries at top; the sphenopalantine artery at the back, and the anterior ethoidal artery and the superior labial artery over the cartilage. These arteries join together at [[Kiesselbach's plexus]].|alt=]]\n\nThe blood supply to the nose is provided by branches of the [[Ophthalmic artery|ophthalmic]], [[Maxillary artery|maxillary]], and [[facial artery|facial arteries]] \u2013 branches of the [[carotid arteries]]. Branches of these arteries [[Circulatory anastomosis|anastomose]] to form [[plexus]]es in and under the nasal mucosa.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> In the septal region [[Kiesselbach's plexus]] is a common site of nosebleeds.\n\nBranches of the ophthalmic artery \u2013 the [[anterior ethmoidal artery|anterior]] and [[posterior ethmoidal artery|posterior ethmoidal arteries]] supply the roof, upper bony septum, and ethmoidal and frontal sinuses. The anterior ethmoidal artery also helps to supply the lower septal cartilage.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Another branch is the [[dorsal nasal artery]] a terminal branch that supplies the skin of the alae and dorsum.\n\nBranches of the maxillary artery include the [[greater palatine artery]]; the [[sphenopalatine artery]] and its  branches \u2013 the [[posterior lateral nasal arteries]] and [[Posterior septal branches of sphenopalatine artery|posterior septal nasal branches]]; the pharyngeal branch; and the [[infraorbital artery]] and its branches \u2013 the superior anterior and posterior alveolar arteries.\n\nThe sphenopalatine artery and the ethmoid arteries supply the outer walls of the nasal cavity. There is additional supply from a branch of the facial artery \u2013 the superior labial artery. The sphenopalantine artery is the artery primarily responsible for supplying the nasal mucosa.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\nThe skin of the alae is supplied by the septal and [[lateral nasal branch of facial artery|lateral nasal branches of the facial artery]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The skin of the outer parts of the alae and the dorsum of the nose are supplied by the [[dorsal nasal artery]] a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and the infraorbital branch of the maxillary arteries.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Drainage===\nVeins of the nose include the [[angular vein]] that drains the side of the nose, receiving lateral nasal veins from the alae. The angular vein joins with the [[superior labial vein]]. Some small veins from the dorsum of the nose drain to the [[Frontal vein|nasal arch]] of the [[frontal vein]] at the root of the nose.\n\nIn the posterior region of the cavity, specifically in the posterior part of the inferior meatus is a [[venous plexus]] known as [[Woodruff's plexus]].<ref name=\"Solomon\">{{cite web |last1=Solomon |first1=Atyam |title=Woodruff plexus {{!}} Radiology Reference Article {{!}} Radiopaedia.org |url=https://radiopaedia.org/articles/woodruff-plexus?lang=gb |website=Radiopaedia |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> This plexus is made up of large thin-walled veins with little soft tissue such as muscle or fiber. The mucosa of the plexus is thin with very few structures.<ref name=\"Chiu\">{{cite journal |last1=Chiu |first1=TW |last2=Shaw-Dunn |first2=J |last3=McGarry |first3=GW |title=Woodruff's plexus. |journal=The Journal of Laryngology and Otology |date=October 2008 |volume=122 |issue=10 |pages=1074\u20137 |doi=10.1017/S002221510800176X |pmid=18289456}}</ref>\n\n==Lymphatic drainage==\nFrom different areas of the nose superficial [[lymphatic vessel]]s run with the veins, and deep lymphatic vessels travel with the arteries.<ref name=\"Moore K\">{{cite book |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=865\u2013867|title=Clinically Oriented Anatomy|last1=Moore|first1=Keith L.|last2=Agur|first2=A. M. R.|last3=Dalley (Ii)|first3=Arthur F.|date=September 2017}}</ref>\n[[Lymph]] drains from the anterior half of the nasal cavity, including both the medial and lateral walls,<ref name=\"Singh\" /> to join that of the external nasal skin to drain into the \n[[submandibular lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The rest of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses all drain to the upper [[deep cervical lymph nodes]], either directly or through the [[retropharyngeal lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> The back of the nasal floor probably drains to the [[parotid lymph nodes]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n==Nerve supply==\nThe nerve supply to the nose and paranasal sinuses comes from two branches of the [[trigeminal nerve]] (CN V): the [[ophthalmic nerve]] (CN V<sub>1</sub>), the [[maxillary nerve]] (CN V<sub>2</sub>), and branches from these.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nIn the nasal cavity, the nasal mucosa is divided in terms of nerve supply into a back lower part (posteroinferior), and a frontal upper part (anterosuperior). The posterior part is supplied by a branch of the maxillary nerve \u2013 the [[nasopalatine nerve]] which reaches the septum. Lateral nasal branches of the [[greater palatine nerve]] supply the lateral wall.\n<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe frontal upper part is supplied from a branch of the ophthalmic nerve \u2013 the  [[nasociliary nerve]], and its branches \u2013 the [[anterior ethmoidal nerve|anterior]] and [[posterior ethmoidal nerve]]s.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nMost of the external nose \u2013 the dorsum, and the apex are supplied by the [[infratrochlear nerve]], (a branch of the nasociliary nerve).<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /><ref name=\"Moore\"/> The external branch of the anterior ethmoidal nerve also supplies areas of skin between the root and the alae.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe alae of the nose are supplied by nasal branches of CN V<sub>2</sub>, the [[infraorbital nerve]], and [[internal nasal branches of infraorbital nerve]] that supply the septum and the vestibule.<ref name=\"Hu\">{{cite journal |last1=Hu |first1=KS |last2=Kwak |first2=J |last3=Koh |first3=KS |last4=Abe |first4=S |last5=Fontaine |first5=C |last6=Kim |first6=HJ |title=Topographic distribution area of the infraorbital nerve. |journal=Surgical and radiologic anatomy : SRA |date=July 2007 |volume=29 |issue=5 |pages=383-8 |doi=10.1007/s00276-007-0227-z |pmid=17585363}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\nThe [[maxillary sinus]] is supplied by [[superior alveolar nerves]] from the maxillary and infraorbital nerves.<ref name=\"Moore\"/><ref name=\"Dorland's\">{{cite book |title=Dorland's illustrated medical dictionary. |publisher=Saunders/Elsevier |isbn=9781416062578 |page=1254 |edition=32nd}}</ref> The [[frontal sinus]] is supplied by branches of the [[supraorbital nerve]].<ref name=\"Moore\"/> The [[ethmoid sinus]]es are supplied by anterior and posterior ethmoid branches of the nasociliary nerve.<ref name=\"Moore\"/> The [[sphenoid sinus]] is supplied by the posterior ethmoidal nerves.<ref name=\"Moore\"/>\n\n===Movement===\nThe muscles of the nose are supplied by branches of the [[facial nerve]]. The [[nasalis muscle]] is supplied by the [[buccal branches of the facial nerve|buccal branches]]. It may also be supplied by one of the [[zygomatic branches of the facial nerve|zygomatic branches]]. The [[procerus]] is supplied by [[temporal branches of the facial nerve]] and lower zygomatic branches; a supply from the buccal branch has also been described. The [[depressor septi]] is innervated by the buccal branch, and sometimes by the zygomatic branch, of the facial nerve. The [[levator labii superioris alaeque nasi]] is innervated by zygomatic and superior buccal branches of the facial nerve.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Smell===\nThe [[Olfaction|sense of smell]] is transmitted by the [[olfactory nerve]]s.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> Olfactory nerves are bundles of very small unmyelinated axons that are derived from [[olfactory receptor neuron]]s in the [[olfactory mucosa]]. The axons are in varying stages of maturity, reflecting the constant turnover of neurons in the olfactory epithelium. A plexiform network is formed in the lamina propria, by the bundles of axons that are surrounded by olfactory ensheathing cells. In as many as twenty branches, the bundled axons cross the cribriform plate and enter the overlying olfactory bulb ending as glomeruli. Each branch is enclosed by an outer dura mater that becomes continuous with the nasal periosteum.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n===Autonomic supply===\nThe nasal mucosa in the nasal cavity is also supplied by the [[autonomic nervous system]].<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" /> [[Postganglionic nerve fibers]] from the [[deep petrosal nerve]] join  with [[preganglionic nerve fibers]] from the [[greater petrosal nerve]] to form the [[nerve of the pterygoid canal]].  Sympathetic postganglionic fibers are distributed to the blood vessels of the nose.  Postganglionic parasympathetic fibres derived from the pterygopalatine ganglion provide the [[secretomotor]] supply to the nasal mucous glands, and are distributed via branches of the maxillary nerves.<ref name=\"Gray's2016\" />\n\n==Development==\n[[Image:Gray45.png|thumb|The [[prenatal development|developing head]] at about four weeks. The olfactory pit can be seen at the top.]]\n\n===Development of the nose===\nIn the early development of the embryo, neural crest cells migrate to form the mesenchymal tissue as [[ectomesenchyme]] of the [[pharyngeal arch]]es.\u00a0 By the end of the fourth week, the first pair of pharyngeal arches form five facial prominences or processes - an unpaired [[frontonasal process]], paired mandibular processes and paired maxillary processes.<ref name=Sadler>{{Cite book|title=Langman's Medical Embryology|last=Sadler|first=T|publisher=|year=2006|isbn=9780781790697|location=|pages=280\u2013284}}</ref><ref name=Larsen>{{Cite book|title=Human Embryology|last=Larsen|first=W|publisher=|year=2001|isbn=0443065837|location=|pages=365\u2013371}}</ref>\u00a0The nose is largely formed by the fusion of these five facial prominences. The frontonasal process gives rise to the bridge of the nose. The medial nasal processes provide the crest and the tip of the nose, and the lateral nasal processes form the alae or sides of the nose. The frontonasal process is a proliferation of mesenchyme in front of\u00a0 the brain vesicles,<ref name=Sadler /> and makes up the upper border of the stomadeum.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\n\nDuring the fifth week the [[maxillary prominence|maxillary process]]es increase in size and at the same time the ectoderm of\u00a0 the frontonasal process becomes thickened at its sides and also increases in size,\u00a0 forming the nasal placodes. The nasal placodes are also known as the olfactory placodes. This development is induced by the ventral part of the forebrain.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\nIn the sixth week the ectoderm in each nasal placode invaginates to form an indented oval-shaped pit, which forms a\u00a0 surrounding\u00a0 raised ridge of tissue.<ref name=Larsen /> Each nasal pit forms a\u00a0 division between the ridges,\u00a0into a lateral nasal process on the outer edge, and a medial nasal process on the inner edge.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\n\nIn the sixth week the nasal pits deepen as they penetrate into the underlying mesenchyme.<ref name=Sadler />\u00a0At this time, the medial nasal processes migrate towards each other and fuse forming the primordium of the bridge of the nose and the septum.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0The migration is helped by the increased growth of the maxillary prominences medially, which compresses the medial nasal processes towards the midline.\u00a0 Their merging takes place at the surface, and also at a deeper level.<ref name=Sadler /> The merge forms the [[intermaxillary segment]], and this is continuous with the rostral part of the nasal septum. The tips of the maxillary processes also grow and fuse with the intermaxillary process. The intermaxillary process gives rise to the [[philtrum]] of the upper lip.<ref name=Sadler />\n\nAt the end of the sixth week the nasal pits have deepened further and they fuse to make a large ectodermal nasal sac. This sac will be above and to the back of the intermaxillary process. Leading into the seventh week, the nasal sac floor and posterior wall grow to form a thickened plate-like ectodermal structure called the nasal fin.<ref name=Larsen /> The nasal fin separates the sac from the oral cavity. Within the fin, vacuoles develop that fuse with the nasal sac. This enlarges the nasal sac and at the same time thins the fin to a membrane - the oronasal membrane that separates the nasal pits from the oral cavity.<ref name=Larsen /> During the seventh week the oronasal membrane ruptures and disintegrates to form an opening - the single primitive choana.\u00a0 The intermaxillary segment extends posteriorly to form the primary palate which makes up the floor of the nasal cavity.<ref name=Larsen /> During the eighth and ninth weeks a pair of thin extensions form from the medial walls of the maxillary process. These extensions are called the palatine shelves that form the secondary palate.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen /> The secondary palate will endochondrally ossify to form the hard palate - the end-stage floor of the nasal cavity.\u00a0 During this time ectoderm and mesoderm of the frontonasal process produce the midline septum. The septum grows down from the roof of the nasal cavity and fuses with the developing palates along the midline. The septum divides the nasal cavity into two nasal passages opening into the pharynx through the definitive choanae.<ref name=Sadler /><ref name=Larsen />\n\nAt ten weeks, the cells differentiate into [[muscle]], [[cartilage]], and [[bone]]. Problems at this stage of development can cause [[birth defect]]s such as [[choanal atresia]] (absent or closed passage), [[facial cleft]]s and [[facial cleft|nasal dysplasia]] (faulty or incomplete development)<ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Hengerer AS, Oas RE |title=Congenital Anomalies of the Nose: Their Embryology, Diagnosis, and Management (SIPAC) |publisher=American Academy of Otolaryngology |location=Alexandria VA |year=1987 }}{{page needed|date=October 2015}}</ref> or extremely rarely polyrrhinia the formation of a duplicate nose.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polyrrhinia (Concept Id: C4274730) - MedGen - NCBI |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/medgen/894825 |website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov |language=en}}</ref>\n\nNormal [[prenatal development|development]] is critical because the newborn infant breathes through the nose for the first six weeks, and any nasal blockage will need emergency treatment to clear.<ref>{{EMedicine|article|835134|Nasal Anatomy}}</ref>\n\n===Development of the paranasal sinuses===\nThe four pairs of [[paranasal sinuses]] - the maxillary, ethmoid, sphenoid, and frontal, develop from the nasal cavity as invaginations extending into their named bones. Two pairs of sinuses form during prenatal development and two pairs form after birth. The maxillary sinuses are the first to appear during the fetal third month. They slowly expand within the maxillary bones and continue to expand throughout childhood.\u00a0The maxillary sinuses form as invaginations from the nasal sac. The ethmoid sinuses appear in the fetal fifth month as invaginations of the middle meatus. The ethmoid sinuses do not grow into the ethmoid bone and do not completely develop until puberty.<ref name=Larsen />\u00a0\n\nThe sphenoid sinuses are extensions of the ethmoid sinuses into the sphenoid bones. They begin to develop around two years of age, and continue to enlarge during childhood.<ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nThe frontal sinuses only develop in the fifth or sixth year of childhood, and continue expanding throughout adolescence. Each frontal sinus is made up of two independent spaces that develop from two different sources; one from the expansion of ethmoid sinuses into frontal bone, and the other develops from invagination. They never coalesce so drain independently.<ref name=Larsen />\n\n==Function==\n\n=== Respiration ===\n[[File:Mouth and pharynx.png|thumb|Air enters the upper respiratory tract through the nose. The nasal conchae can be seen in this image.]]\nThe nose is the first organ of the [[Respiratory tract|upper respiratory tract]] in the [[respiratory system]]. Its main respiratory function is the supply and conditioning, by warming, moisturising and filtering of [[particulate]]s of inhaled air.<ref name=\"Saladin\"/> [[Nasal hair]] in the nostrils traps large particles preventing their entry into the lungs.<ref name=\"anatomy\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=K |title=Human anatomy |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780071222075 |pages=633\u2013636 |edition=3rd|year=2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe three positioned [[nasal conchae]] in each cavity provide four grooves as air passages, along which the air is circulated and moved to the [[nasopharynx]].<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\">{{cite journal |last1=Van Cauwenberge |first1=P |last2=Sys |first2=L |last3=De Belder |first3=T |last4=Watelet |first4=JB |title=Anatomy and physiology of the nose and the paranasal sinuses. |journal=Immunology and Allergy Clinics of North America |date=February 2004 |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317 |doi=10.1016/S0889-8561(03)00107-3 |pmid=15062424}}</ref> The internal structures and cavities, including the conchae and paranasal sinuses form an integrated system for the conditioning of the air breathed in through the nose.<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\" /> This functioning also includes the major role of the [[nasal mucosa]], and the resulting conditioning of the air before it reaches the lungs is important in maintaining the internal environment and proper functioning of the lungs.<ref name=\"Sahin-Yilmaz\">{{cite journal |last1=Sahin-Yilmaz |first1=A |last2=Naclerio |first2=RM |title=Anatomy and physiology of the upper airway. |journal=Proceedings of the American Thoracic Society |date=March 2011 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=31\u20139 |doi=10.1513/pats.201007-050RN |pmid=21364219}}</ref> The turbulence created by the conchae and meatuses optimises the warming, moistening, and filtering of the mucosa.<ref name=\"Bettejewski\">{{cite journal |last1=Betlejewski |first1=S |last2=Betlejewski |first2=A |title=[The influence of nasal flow aerodynamics on the nasal physiology]. |journal=Otolaryngologia Polska = the Polish Otolaryngology |date=2008 |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=321\u20135 |doi=10.1016/S0030-6657(08)70263-4 |pmid=18652158}}</ref> A major protective role is thereby provided by these structures of the upper respiratory tract, in the passage of air to the more delicate structures of the lower respiratory tract.<ref name=\"Van Cauwenberge\" />\n\n[[Sneeze|Sneezing]] is an important protective [[reflex action]] initiated by irritation of the [[mucous membrane of nose|nasal mucosa]] to expel unwanted particles through the mouth and nose.<ref name=\"Songu\">{{cite journal |last1=Songu |first1=M |last2=Cingi |first2=C |title=Sneeze reflex: facts and fiction. |journal=Therapeutic Advances in Respiratory Disease |date=June 2009 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=131\u201341 |doi=10.1177/1753465809340571 |pmid=19617285}}</ref> [[Photic sneeze reflex|Photic sneezing]] is a reflex brought on by different stimuli such as bright lights.<ref name=\"Garcia-Moreno\">{{cite journal |date=January 2006 |pmid=16525923|last1=Garc\u00eda-Moreno|first1=J. M.|title=Photic sneeze reflex or autosomal dominant compelling helio-ophthalmic outburst syndrome|journal=Neurologia (Barcelona, Spain)|volume=21|issue=1|pages=26\u201333}}</ref> The nose is also able to provide sense information as to the temperature of the air being breathed.<ref name=\"Geurkink\">{{cite journal |last1=Geurkink |first1=N |title=Nasal anatomy, physiology, and function. |journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology |date=August 1983 |volume=72 |issue=2 |pages=123\u20138 |pmid=6350406|doi=10.1016/0091-6749(83)90518-3 }}</ref>\n\n===Sense of smell===\n[[File:1403 Olfaction.jpg|thumb|The cells lining the nose involved in smell ([[olfaction]]) are shown here]]\nThe nose also plays the major part in the [[olfactory system]]. It contains an area of specialised cells, [[olfactory receptor neuron]]s responsible for the [[sense]] of smell ([[olfaction]]). [[Olfactory mucosa]] in the upper nasal cavity, contains a type of [[nasal glands|nasal gland]] called [[olfactory gland]]s or Bowman's glands which help in olfaction. The nasal conchae also help in olfaction function, by directing air-flow to the olfactory region.<ref name=\"Bettejewski\"/><ref name=Bluestone>{{cite book|last=Bluestone|first=Charles|title=Pediatric otolaryngology|year=2002|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-7216-9197-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y5rpEdeKtJEC&pg=PA879&dq=nasal+glands#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Speech===\n{{Main|Speech}}\nNormal [[speech]] is produced with pressure from the lungs. This can be modified using airflow through the nose in a process called [[nasalisation]]. This involves the lowering of the soft palate to produce [[nasal vowel]]s and [[Nasal consonant|consonants]] by allowing air to escape from both the nose and the mouth.<ref name=\"Ohala\">{{cite web |last1=Ohala |first1=John |title=The Phonetics of Nasal Phonology:Theorems and Data |url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~ohala/papers/nasal93.pdf |website=berkeley.edu |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> Nasal airflow is also used to produce a variety of [[nasal click]]s called [[click consonant]]s.<ref name=\"Laver\">{{cite book |last1=Laver |first1=John |last2=John |first2=Laver |title=Principles of Phonetics |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zxKCbu536Z8C&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=nasal+clicks#v=onepage&q=nasal%20clicks&f=false |publisher=Cambridge University Press |accessdate=27 November 2019 |language=en |date=12 May 1994|isbn=9780521456555 }}</ref> The large, hollow cavities of the paranasal sinuses act as [[resonance|resonating]] chambers that modify, and amplify speech and other vocal vibrations passing through them.<ref name=\"Saladin2012\">{{cite book |last1=Saladin |first1=Kenneth |title=Anatomy & physiology : the unity of form and function |date=2012 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=9780073378251 |pages=856 |edition=6th}}</ref><ref name=\"T and D\">{{cite book |last1=Tortora |first1=G |title=Principles of anatomy & physiology. |date=2011 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=9780470646083 |page=875 |edition=13th.}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\nOne of the most common medical conditions involving the nose is a [[nosebleed]] (epistaxis). Most nosebleeds occur in [[Kiesselbach's plexus]], a vascular plexus in the lower front part of the septum involving the [[anastamosis|convergence]] of four [[artery|arteries]]. A smaller proportion of nosebleeds that tend to be nontraumatic, occur in [[Woodruff's plexus]]. Woodruff's plexus is a [[venous plexus]] of large thin-walled [[vein]]s lying in the posterior part of the inferior meatus.<ref name=\"Chiu\" />\n\nAnother common condition is [[nasal congestion]], usually a symptom of infection, particularly [[sinusitis]], or other inflammation of the nasal lining called [[rhinitis]], including [[allergic rhinitis]] and [[nonallergic rhinitis]]. Chronic nasal obstruction resulting in breathing through the mouth can greatly impair or prevent the nostrils from flaring.<ref name=\"COA\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Keith |last2=Dalley |first2=Arthur |last3=Agur |first3=Anne |title=Clinically oriented anatomy |date=2018 |publisher=Wolters Kluwer |isbn=9781496347213 |pages=864\u2013869 |edition=Eighth}}</ref> One of the causes of [[snoring]] is nasal obstruction,<ref name=\"mayoclinic\">\"{{cite web |url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/snoring/basics/causes/con-20031874 |title=Snoring Causes |publisher=Mayo Clinic |date=26 April 2015 |website=Mayo Clinic |access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref> and anti-snoring devices such as a [[nasal strip]] help to flare the nostrils and keep the airway open.<ref name=\"COA\"/> '''Nasal flaring''' usually seen in children, happens when breathing is difficult.<ref name=\"flaring\">{{cite web |title=Nasal flaring: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia |url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003055.htm |website=medlineplus.gov |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Most conditions of nasal congestion also cause a loss of the sense of smell ([[anosmia]]). This may also occur in other conditions, for example following trauma, in [[Kallmann syndrome]] or [[Parkinson's disease]]. A blocked sinus ostium, an opening from a paranasal sinus, will cause fluid to accumulate in the sinus.\n\nIn children the nose is a common site of [[foreign bodies]].<ref name=\"urlForeign Body, Nose\">{{cite web |url=http://www.emedicinehealth.com/foreign_body_nose/article_em.htm |title=Foreign Body, Nose |accessdate=2008-12-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220030033/http://www.emedicinehealth.com/foreign_body_nose/article_em.htm |archivedate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> The nose is one of the exposed areas that is susceptible to [[frostbite]].<ref name=\"mayo\">{{cite web |title=Frostbite - Symptoms and causes |url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/frostbite/symptoms-causes/syc-20372656 |website=Mayo Clinic |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the special nature of the blood supply to the human nose and surrounding area, it is possible for retrograde infections from the nasal area to spread to the brain. For this reason, the area from the corners of the mouth to the bridge of the nose, including the nose and [[maxilla]], is known as the [[danger triangle of the face]].<ref name=\"Moore\" />\n\nInfections or other conditions that may result in destruction of, or damage to a part of the nose include [[rhinophyma]],<ref name=\"T\u00fcz\u00fcn\">{{cite journal |last1=T\u00fcz\u00fcn |first1=Y |last2=Wolf |first2=R |last3=Kutlubay |first3=Z |last4=Karaku\u015f |first4=O |last5=Engin |first5=B |title=Rosacea and rhinophyma. |journal=Clinics in Dermatology |date=October 2014 |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201346 |doi=10.1016/j.clindermatol.2013.05.024 |pmid=24314376}}</ref> [[skin cancer]]s particularly [[basal-cell carcinoma]],<ref name=\"BSF\">{{cite web |title=Basal Cell Carcinoma |url=https://www.britishskinfoundation.org.uk/bcc |website=British Skin Foundation |language=en}}</ref> [[paranasal sinus and nasal cavity cancer]],<ref name=\"NCI\">{{cite web |title=Paranasal Sinus and Nasal Cavity Cancer Treatment (Adult) (PDQ\u00ae)\u2013Patient Version |url=https://www.cancer.gov/types/head-and-neck/patient/adult/paranasal-sinus-treatment-pdq#_1 |website=National Cancer Institute |language=en |date=8 November 2019}}</ref> [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]],<ref name=\"Coordes\"/> [[syphilis]],<ref name=\"Woods\">{{cite journal |last1=Woods |first1=CR |title=Congenital syphilis-persisting pestilence. |journal=The Pediatric Infectious Disease Journal |date=June 2009 |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=536\u20137 |doi=10.1097/INF.0b013e3181ac8a69 |pmid=19483520 }}</ref> [[leprosy]],{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} [[recreational drug use|recreational use of cocaine]],<ref name=\"Trimarchi\">{{cite journal |last1=Trimarchi |first1=M |last2=Bussi |first2=M |last3=Sinico |first3=RA |last4=Meroni |first4=P |last5=Specks |first5=U |title=Cocaine-induced midline destructive lesions - an autoimmune disease? |journal=Autoimmunity Reviews |date=February 2013 |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=496\u2013500 |doi=10.1016/j.autrev.2012.08.009 |pmid=22940554}}</ref> [[chromium]] and other toxins.<ref name=\"Feron\">{{cite journal |last1=Feron |first1=VJ |last2=Arts |first2=JH |last3=Kuper |first3=CF |last4=Slootweg |first4=PJ |last5=Woutersen |first5=RA |title=Health risks associated with inhaled nasal toxicants. |journal=Critical Reviews in Toxicology |date=May 2001 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=313\u201347 |doi=10.1080/20014091111712 |pmid=11405443}}</ref> The nose may be stimulated to grow in [[acromegaly]], a condition caused by an excess of [[growth hormone]].<ref name=\"NIDDK\">{{cite web |title=Acromegaly {{!}} NIDDK |url=https://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/endocrine-diseases/acromegaly?dkrd=hispt0293 |website=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases}}</ref>\n\nA common anatomic variant is an air-filled cavity within a concha known as a [[concha bullosa]].<ref name=\"Cukurova\">{{cite journal |last1=Cukurova |first1=I |last2=Yaz |first2=A |last3=Gumussoy |first3=M |last4=Yigitbasi |first4=OG |last5=Karaman |first5=Y |title=A patient presenting with concha bullosa in another concha bullosa: a case report. |journal=Journal of Medical Case Reports |date=26 March 2012 |volume=6 |pages=87 |doi=10.1186/1752-1947-6-87 |pmid=22448660|pmc=3338398 }}</ref> In rare cases a polyp can form inside a bullosa.<ref name=\"Erkan\">{{cite journal |last1=Erkan |first1=AN |last2=Canbolat |first2=T |last3=Ozer |first3=C |last4=Yilmaz |first4=I |last5=Ozluoglu |first5=LN |title=Polyp in concha bullosa: a case report and review of the literature. |journal=Head & Face Medicine |date=8 May 2006 |volume=2 |pages=11 |doi=10.1186/1746-160X-2-11 |pmid=16681852|pmc=1471777 }}</ref> Usually a concha bullosa is small and without symptoms but when large can cause obstruction to sinus drainage.<ref name=\"Tapia\">{{cite journal |last1=Rodrigo Tapia |first1=JP |last2=Alvarez Alvarez |first2=I |last3=Casas Rubio |first3=C |last4=Blanco Mercad\u00e9 |first4=A |last5=D\u00edaz Villarig |first5=JL |title=[A giant bilateral concha bullosa causing nasal obstruction]. |journal=Acta Otorrinolaringologica Espanola |date=August 1999 |volume=50 |issue=6 |pages=490\u20132 |pmid=10502705}}</ref>\n\nSome drugs can be [[nasal administration|nasally administered]], and these include [[nasal spray]]s and [[topical medication|topical treatments]].<ref name=\"Geurkink\" /><ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=N |title=The nose and paranasal sinuses physiology and anatomy. |journal=Advanced Drug Delivery Reviews |date=23 September 2001 |volume=51 |issue=1\u20133 |pages=5\u201319 |pmid=11516776|doi=10.1016/S0169-409X(01)00172-7 }}</ref> The septal cartilage can be destroyed through the repeated inhalation of [[recreational drug]]s such as [[cocaine]].  This, in turn, can lead to more widespread collapse of the nasal skeleton.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Menick|first=F|date=November 2014|title=Primary intranasal lining injury cause, deformities, and treatment plan.|url=|journal=Plast Reconstr Surg|volume=134|issue=5|pages=1045\u201356|pmid=25347637|doi=10.1097/PRS.0000000000000694}}</ref>\n\n[[Sneeze|Sneezing]] can transmit infections carried in the expelled droplets. This route is called either [[Transmission (medicine)|airborne transmission]] or [[aerosol]] transmission.<ref name=\"Tellier\">{{cite journal |last1=Tellier |first1=R |last2=Li |first2=Y |last3=Cowling |first3=BJ |last4=Tang |first4=JW |title=Recognition of aerosol transmission of infectious agents: a commentary. |journal=BMC Infectious Diseases |date=31 January 2019 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=101 |doi=10.1186/s12879-019-3707-y |pmid=30704406|pmc=6357359 }}</ref>\n\n===Surgical procedures===\n{{Further|Rhinoplasty}}\n[[File: Ivory artificial nose, Europe, 1701-1800 Wellcome L0058564.jpg|thumb|upright=0.4|[[Prosthesis|Prosthetic nose]] from 17th century Europe.]]\nBadly positioned alar cartilages lack proper support, and can affect the function of the external nasal valve. This can cause breathing problems particularly during deep inhalation.<ref name=\"Silva\">{{cite journal |last1=Silva |first1=EN |title=The Relation Between the Lower Lateral Cartilages and the Function of the External Nasal Valve. |journal=Aesthetic Plastic Surgery |date=February 2019 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=175\u2013183 |doi=10.1007/s00266-018-1195-x |pmid=30019240}}</ref> The surgical procedure to correct breathing problems due to disorders in the nasal structures is called a [[rhinoplasty]], and this is also the procedure used for a [[plastic surgery|cosmetic surgery]] when it is commonly called a \"nose job\". For surgical procedures of rhinoplasty, the nose is mapped out into a number of [[Rhinoplasty|subunits and segments]]. This uses nine ''aesthetic nasal subunits'' and six ''aesthetic nasal segments''. A [[septoplasty]] is the specific surgery to correct a [[nasal septum deviation]].\n\nA [[nasal fracture|broken nose]] can result from trauma. Minor fractures may heal on their own. Surgery known as [[Reduction (orthopedic surgery)|reduction]] may be carried out on more severe breaks that cause dislocation.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=26770280|pmc=4702055|year=2015|last1=K\u00fchnel|first1=T. S.|title=Trauma of the midface|journal=GMS Current Topics in Otorhinolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery|volume=14|pages=Doc06|last2=Reichert|first2=T. E.|doi=10.3205/cto000121}}</ref>\n\nSeveral nasal procedures of the nose and paranasal sinuses can be carried out using [[minimally-invasive procedure|minimally-invasive]] nasal [[endoscope|endoscopy]]. These procedures aim to restore sinus ventilation, mucociliary clearance, and maintain the health of the sinus mucosa.<ref name=\"Kumar\">{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=A |last2=Yadav |first2=N |last3=Singh |first3=N |last4=Chauhan |first4=N |title=Minimally invasive (endoscopic-computer assisted) surgery:Technique and review |journal=Annals of Maxillofacial Surgery |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=159\u2013164 |date=December 2016 |pmid=28299251 |pmc=5343621 |doi=10.4103/2231-0746.200348 }}</ref>\nSome non-nasal surgeries can also be carried out through the use of an endoscope that is entered through the nose. These [[Endoscopic endonasal surgery|endoscopic endonasal surgeries]] are used to remove tumours from the front of the base of the skull.<ref name=\"Komotar\">{{cite journal |last1=Komotar |first1=RJ |last2=Starke |first2=RM |last3=Raper |first3=DM |last4=Anand |first4=VK |last5=Schwartz |first5=TH |title=Endoscopic endonasal compared with microscopic transsphenoidal and open transcranial resection of craniopharyngiomas. |journal=World Neurosurgery |date=February 2012 |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=329\u201341 |doi=10.1016/j.wneu.2011.07.011 |pmid=22501020}}</ref>\n\nSwollen conchae can cause obstruction and [[nasal congestion]], and may be treated surgically by a [[turbinectomy]].<ref name=\"Ye\">{{cite journal |last1=Ye |first1=T |last2=Zhou |first2=B |title=Update on surgical management of adult inferior turbinate hypertrophy. |journal=Current Opinion in Otolaryngology & Head and Neck Surgery |date=February 2015 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=29\u201333 |doi=10.1097/MOO.0000000000000130 |pmid=25565284}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nSome people choose to have [[plastic surgery|cosmetic surgery]] called a [[rhinoplasty]], to change the appearance of their nose. [[Nose piercing]]s are also common, such as in the nostril, septum, or bridge. In certain [[Asia]]n countries such as China, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Thailand and Bangladesh, rhinoplasties are commonly carried out to create a more developed nose bridge or a \"high nose\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/article/1053286/miss-universe-malaysia-pageant-contestants-look-too-western |title=Miss Universe Malaysia pageant contestants 'look too western' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922182526/http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/article/1053286/miss-universe-malaysia-pageant-contestants-look-too-western|archivedate=2016-09-22|date=2018-11-28 }}</ref> Similarly, \"[[Do it yourself|DIY]] nose lifts\" in the form of re-usable cosmetic items have become popular and are sold in many Asian countries such as China, Japan, South Korea, Taiwan, Sri Lanka and Thailand.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/06/diy-plastic-surgery-can-you-change-your-face-without-going-under-the-knife |title=DIY Plastic Surgery: Can You Change Your Face Without Going Under the Knife?|first=Nina |last=Strochlic |date=6 January 2014 |publisher= |newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/thailand/bangkok-post/20161227/282467118553578 |title=Connecting People Through News |website=PressReader |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135827/https://www.pressreader.com/thailand/bangkok-post/20161227/282467118553578 |archivedate=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shybuy.lk/product_info.php/products_id/143|title=Nose Shaper|website=Shybuy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605113816/http://shybuy.lk/product_info.php/products_id/143|archivedate=2017-06-05|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref> A high-bridged nose has been a common beauty ideal in many Asian cultures dating back to the beauty ideals of ancient China and India.<ref>{{cite book|author=Marc S. Abramson|title=Ethnic Identity in Tang China |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-GLGnRspmcAC&pg=PA88|year=2011|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-0101-7 |page=88 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502191609/https://books.google.com/books?id=-GLGnRspmcAC&pg=PA88|archivedate=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Johann Jakob Meyer|title=Sexual Life in Ancient India: A Study in the Comparative History of Indian Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izFNswlJ9LMC&pg=PA433|year=1989|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0638-2 |page=433 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502191609/https://books.google.com/books?id=izFNswlJ9LMC&pg=PA433|archivedate=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn [[New Zealand]], nose pressing (\"[[hongi]]\") is a traditional [[greeting]] originating among the [[M\u0101ori people]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Derby|first1=Mark|title=Ng\u0101 mahi tika|url=https://www.teara.govt.nz/en/nga-mahi-tika|publisher=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=8 September 2017|date=September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908020350/https://www.teara.govt.nz/en/nga-mahi-tika|archivedate=8 September 2017}}</ref> However it is now generally confined to certain traditional celebrations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.polynesia.com/blog/greetings-hongi-style/|title=Greetings! Hongi Style! \u2013 polynesia.com {{!}} blog|date=2016-03-24|work=polynesia.com {{!}} blog|access-date=2017-09-18|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918155352/http://www.polynesia.com/blog/greetings-hongi-style/|archivedate=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hanazuka]] monument enshrines the mutilated noses of at least 38,000 Koreans killed during the Japanese invasions of Korea from 1592 to 1598.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sansom |first=George Bailey |title=A History of Japan, 1334\u20131615 |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofjapan00sans |url-access=registration |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1961 |series=Stanford studies in the civilizations of eastern Asia|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofjapan00sans/page/360 360]|isbn=978-0-8047-0525-7 |quote=Visitors to Kyoto used to be shown the Minizuka or Ear Tomb, which contained, it was said, the noses of those 38,000, sliced off, suitably pickled, and sent to Kyoto as evidence of victory. }}</ref>\n\n[[Nose-picking]] is a common, mildly [[taboo]] habit. Medical risks include the spread of infections, nosebleeds and, rarely, [[nasal septum perforation|perforation of the nasal septum]]. When it becomes compulsive it is termed [[rhinotillexomania]]. The wiping of the nose with the hand, commonly referred to as the \"[[allergic salute]]\", is also mildly taboo and can result in the spreading of infections as well. Habitual as well as fast or rough nose wiping may also result in a crease (known as a [[transverse nasal crease]] or groove) running across the nose, and can lead to permanent physical deformity observable in childhood and adulthood.<ref name=pray221>{{cite book|last=Pray|first=W. Steven |title=Nonprescription Product Therapeutics|year=2005|publisher=[[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]]|location=p. 221|isbn=978-0781734981}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Mitali Ruths |url=http://www.livestrong.com/article/296252-white-line-on-nose-in-children/ |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=2012-11-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622025144/http://www.livestrong.com/article/296252-white-line-on-nose-in-children/ |archivedate=2012-06-22 |title=White Line on Nose in Children |website=LiveStrong.com }}</ref>\n\n[[Nose fetishism]] (or nasophilia) is the sexual [[partialism]] for the nose.<ref name=\"freedict\">{{cite web |title=nasophilia |url=https://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/nasophilia |website=The Free Dictionary}}</ref>\n\n==Neanderthals==\n[[Clive Finlayson]] of the [[Gibraltar Museum]] said the large [[Neanderthal]] noses were an adaption to the cold,<ref>{{cite book | last = Finlayson | first = C | title = Neanderthals and modern humans: an ecological and evolutionary perspective | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-521-82087-5 | pages = [https://books.google.com/books?id=TmQ4i1EQ4AYC&pg=PA84 84] }}</ref> Todd C. Rae of the [[American Museum of Natural History]] said primate and arctic animal studies have shown sinus size reduction in areas of extreme cold rather than enlargement in accordance with [[Allen's rule]].<ref name=\"Rae\" /> Therefore, Todd C. Rae concludes that the design of the large and [[Wiktionary:prognathous#English|prognathic]] Neanderthal nose was evolved for the hotter climate of the Middle East and Africa and remained unchanged when they entered Europe <ref name=\"Rae\">{{cite journal | last1 = Rae | first1 = T.C. | year = 2011 | title = The Neanderthal face is not cold adapted | url = | journal = Journal of Human Evolution | volume = 60 | issue = 2| pages = 234\u2013239 | doi=10.1016/j.jhevol.2010.10.003 | pmid=21183202}}</ref>\n\nMiquel Hern\u00e1ndez of the Department of Animal Biology at the [[University of Barcelona]] said the \"high and narrow nose of [[Eskimos]] and [[Neanderthals]]\" is an \"adaption to a cold and dry environment\", since it contributes to warming and moisturizing the air and the \"recovery of heat and moisture from expired air\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hern\u00e1ndez | first1 = M. | last2 = Fox | first2 = C. L. | last3 = Garcia-Moro | first3 = C. | year = 1997 | title = Fueguian cranial morphology: The adaptation to a cold, harsh environment | url = | journal = American Journal of Physical Anthropology | volume = 103 | issue = 1| pages = 103\u2013117 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1096-8644(199705)103:1<103::AID-AJPA7>3.0.CO;2-X | pmid=9185954}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Empty nose syndrome]], a nose crippled by excessive resection of the inferior and/or middle [[turbinates]] of the nose\n* [[Nasothek]]\n* [[Neti (Hatha Yoga)]], an [[Ayurvedic]] technique of [[nasal irrigation|nasal cleansing]]\n* [[Sr\u00f2n]], the [[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]] word for nose and the name of some hills in the [[Scottish Highlands]]\n\n==References==\n{{Gray's}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Human noses}}\n* {{Wikiquote inline|Noses}}\n\n{{Nose anatomy}}\n{{Human regional anatomy}}\n{{Human systems and organs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Facial features]]\n[[Category:Nose]]\n[[Category:Human anatomy|nose]]\n[[Category:Human head and neck]]\n[[Category:Sensory organs]]\n", "name_user": "Iztwoz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSense of smell:small change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_nose"}
